<FIRST>r a BC-Opera     01-28 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Opera,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Met Performs Season's First `Don Carlo'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand opera as grand as it gets filled the
Metropolitan Opera stage in the first performance this season of
Verdi's ``Don Carlo.''
   James Levine conducted on Friday night, bringing out the opera's
orchestral glories and at times threatening to drown out the
singers. But the soloists had powerful lungs and the large chorus
soared vocally over the orchestra.
   Tenor Neil Shicoff was Don Carlo, betrothed to Elizabeth,
daughter of the French king. After they meet and fall in love they
discover that a treaty has given her to Carlo's father, Philip II of
Spain. The fallout from that, plus the Spanish Inquisition, is
plenty for an opera, even one as long as ``Don Carlo.''
   Shicoff began too loud but quickly settled into a well-sung,
feeling portrayl. Margaret Price sang Elizabeth. Her voice is
beautiful, smooth and large. At the end of the third long scene,
singing to a banished countess, Miss Price sounded tired. But she
recovered before Act 2.
   Both Shicoff and Miss Price were singing their parts for the
first time at the Met.
   Baritone Bernd Weikl as Rodrigo was more brusque than subtle. He
sounded as though he were pushing for volume. Ruggero Raimondi, his
voice very focused, was impressive as King Philip.
   Tatiana Troyanos, always a favorite of the Met audience, was fine
as Princess Eboli. She didn't wear the eye patch that was part of
the costume when this production was new 10 years ago. The real
Eboli wore one but since ``Don Carlo'' is more drama than history
and the stage eye patch was distracting, Miss Troyanos was better
off without it.
   The auto-da-fe scene was lavish with clerics, onlookers and flag
wavers. The royals and Grand Inquisitor (Jan-Hendrik Rootering) wore
black trimmed in gold. Hei-Kyung Hong sounded celestial as the
celestial voice. However, in this staging, she welcomed those burned
into heaven before anybody lighted the fire.
   ``Don Carlo'' was last sung at the Met during the 1985-86 season.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
