<FIRST>r a PM-PresidentialPorkRinds     01-28 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Presidential Pork Rinds,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Pork Rind Processor Going for Capitol Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the largest processors of George Bush's
favorite snack food is hoping to catapult the product to national
popularity with a new brand: Presidential Pork Rinds.
   ``I'll be on the street with them next week,'' Bill Connor, sales
manager for Evans Food Products Co., said Friday.
   The brand is a take-off on the president's well-known
predilection for the porcine product. A gift jar of pork rinds
replaced Ronald Reagan's crystal container of jellybeans on the
table at Bush's first Cabinet meeting this week.
   ``George Bush has done wonders for pork rinds here this year,''
said Al Rickard, a spokesman for the Snack Food Association in
Alexandria, Va.
   ``My view is, `Skins are in. Pork rinds in '89,''' said Connor,
who sent 3,000 pounds of the crunchy, puffed snack to Washington for
the presidential inaugural ball and in return got an invitation to
the event.
   Pork rinds are fried pieces of hog skin, cooked in hog fat,
stored in pellets for 30 days and fried again for 60 seconds in oil
heated to 400 degrees, ``at which time they explode like popcorn,''
Connor said.
   Evans Food Products, with a plant on Chicago's south side,
supplies pork rind pellets to Dallas-based Frito-Lay, the largest
U.S. marketer of pork rinds, and other companies, Connor said.
   Evans handles about 50 million pounds of pork skin annually.
   He said pork rinds compare favorably to peanuts in fat content
and contain a high percentage of protein. Nutrition experts,
however, say the salted snack has enough calories, fat and sodium to
make it a poor food for all but the most physically active people
with the lowest cholesterol levels.
   The Snack Food Association said pork rind sales totaled $195
million in 1987, a figure dwarfed by sales of potato chips, which
enjoyed $3.8 billion in sales in the $8 billion salty snack food
market.
</TEXT>
