<FIRST>r a PM-StudentsKilled     01-28 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Students Killed,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saddened Students File By Smashed Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKAY, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The collision of two vehicles that killed
three students and a man just 100 yards from the school has brought
many in the town together to mourn.
   Many students stopped by a salvage yard to see the smashed
remains of a classmate's car on Friday, a day after three people
were killed in the vehicle.
   School officials in the town 40 miles southeast of Tulsa called
off classes Thursday and Friday.
   The Rev. Dick Knox of Okay First Baptist Church said there was no
easy way to ease the sorrow felt by friends and families of the
victims.
   ``You just touch them. That's all I know, you just touch them. Be
available and try to be sensitive and touch them however you can,''
he said.
   The Rev. Opal Large of Okay Christian Fellowship said some of the
children had attended services at her church in the town of 600.
   ``It doesn't make any difference if they were in our church or
not. We feel close to everybody in Okay and we love them and want
them to know that,'' she said.
   The Oklahoma Highway Patrol identified the dead as Jason
Branchcomb, 17, of Wagoner; Stephanie Hamby, 17, of Okay; her
brother, Jason Hamby, 14, of Okay and James Risinger, 56, of
Wagoner. Branchcomb's brother, Jeffrey, 11, was in stable condition
at Muskogee Regional Medical Center.
   Troopers said the car driven by Jason Branchcomb went out of
control and collided with the pick-up truck driven by Risinger.
   Most of the 600 students in the school learned of the accident
from the wail of ambulance sirens.
   A school assembly was planned for Monday morning.
</TEXT>
