<DOCNO> AP890128-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 0118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-Gandhi     01-28 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Gandhi,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Defeat Ominous For Gandhi In Election Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The debacle for Rajiv Gandhi's Congress
Party in a major state election this past week was the latest in a
series of reverses for the prime minister, who will face his own
voter test by the end of the year.
   Gandhi, 44, had a dream start as prime minister _ his party won
four-fifths of the 542 seats in Parliament in 1984 _ but allegations
of corruption, a belligerent opposition headed by a former Cabinet
colleague and successive defeats in state elections raise doubts
about his return for a second term.
   The Congress Party has lost 11 of its last 18 state elections.
The latest defeat was Jan. 21 in populous Tamil Nadu state, where it
won only 26 of the 234 state assembly seats.
   ``Gandhi's problem is a failure at the political level,'' said
Bhabani Sengupta, one of India's foremost political analysts. ``It's
a pity because he came in with a tremendous amount of goodwill and a
tremendous amount of promise.''
   In January 1985, the former airline pilot was sworn in as prime
minister after his Congress Party swept the highest number of
parliamentary seats ever won by a single party since India became
independent in 1947.
   The victory was ascribed mainly to the wave of sympathy for
Gandhi after his mother, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, was
assassinated three months earlier.
   But it was helped also by Gandhi's ``Mr. Clean'' image, which
sprang from his age and inexperience in what many people saw as the
dirty world of politics. His stewardship gave the government an
unprecedented honeymoon with the press. Even normally
anti-establishment newspapers were enthusiastic.
   ``The parliamenary election Gandhi won four years ago ... has
created an illusory world for him,'' the Hindustan Times, a usually
pro-government newspaper, said in an editorial this week. ``This
kind of mandate breeds dangerous smugness.''
   The cracks did not appear for almost a year. The first murmurs
against Gandhi began with his inability to solve the lingering
problem of a murderous Sikh insurgency in the northern state of
Punjab.
   The low point came in 1987, when newspapers claimed the Swedish
arms company AB Bofors paid $50 million in bribes to secure a
government contract for artillery guns.
   Gandhi denied involvement. A parliamentary committee cleared the
government of complicity, but the allegations persist and are still
under investigation. In the midst of the allegations, V.P. Singh,
who had held the defense and finance portfolios in Gandhi's Cabinet,
quit the party after building a reputation as a crusader against
corruption.
   Singh went on to win a parliamentary by-election as an
independent running on a clean-government platform. In the past six
months, he has been largely successful in persuading national
opposition parties and regional parties to form a national coalition
opposed to Gandhi.
   In India's 41-year history, no single opposition party has ever
posed a serious threat to the Congress Party. Instead, the
opposition has been splintered among powerful local parties and a
vast array of national parties.
   The only time Congress ever lost a national election was in 1977
when the opposition united after Mrs. Gandhi imposed an emergency
and banned political activity.
   ``If the opposition is united and can present itself as a
creditable alternative, then the Congress (Party) will be in very
serious trouble,'' said Sengupta, the political analyst.
   At least seven parties have joined the anti-Gandhi front, and
together they control seven of India's 25 states. Last week's polls
in Tamil Nadu voted the front's Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam Party into
power, and the Congress trailed a poor third behind another regional
party.
   ``It will be dangerous for the Congress to believe that what
happened in Tamil Nadu was only a regional phenomenon,'' the
Hindustan Times said. ``No state is out of the national mainstream.
What (happens) at the polling booth in Tamil Nadu has also an impact
on the rest of the country.''
</TEXT>
