<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 0129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls     01-28 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swift Action Needed on Insurance Fund, Congressmen Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress are urging President Bush
to reassure savings and loan depositors by swiftly developing a plan
to pump more money into the ailing government insurance fund for
S&amp;Ls.
   ``Public confidence is so precarious today that it is imperative
that a comprehensive approach be presented soon,'' said Rep. Jim
Leach, R-Iowa, the second-ranking Republican on the House Banking
Committee.
   ``The exact nature is not as important as the fact that a serious
package be presented,'' he said.
   Bush sought Friday to stem nervousness following scattered
reports that some S&amp;L depositors withdrew their money after learning
that the administration is considering a 25-cent fee on every $100
in federally insured accounts.
   ``The savings and loan deposits are backed by the full faith and
credit of the government and they are sound, they are good,'' Bush
told reporters at the White House. ``I want to assure the American
people of that and that's not going to change.''
   However, Bush said he has made no decisions on a plan for the S&amp;L
problem and would not rule out the deposit insurance fee.
   ``There seems to be some controversy around it, but that doesn't
mean that any thinking along those lines should cease,'' the
president said.
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, chairman of the House Banking
Committee, said in a statement that the Bush administration's
disarray on the S&amp;L crisis is contributing to a growing nervousness
among depositors.
   ``Savings and loans are receiving a heavy run of calls from
depositors who are confused and concerned about the reports of a new
tax on their deposits,'' Gonzalez said. ``In some areas there have
been higher than expected withdrawals of funds.''
   M. Danny Wall, chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board,
disputed Gonzalez' assertion, saying it was based on ``an inartful
distillation of calls made by somebody on the (committee) staff.''
However, in an interview a day before, Wall said: ``There have been
cases where they (depositors) say, `I don't like what I heard on TV,
I'm taking my money out.'''
   Bank board spokesman Karl Hoyle said a survey of thrift
institutions Thursday night showed ``no outflows of any significance
that we can attribute to anything that's been said.''
   Gonzalez accused the administration of being ``extremely
careless'' in floating the deposit fee trial balloon and called on
Bush to ``take a personal hand in clarifying the administration's
proposal.''
   The Treasury Department has been studying the S&amp;L problem since
the fall and is expected to present Bush with its recommendations
next week. Department officials have been briefing members of
Congress on some of the options under consideration, in addition to
a deposit fee.
   Rep. Stan Parris, R-Va., a senior member of the banking
committee, said Treasury is talking about borrowing about $45
billion, roughly the amount needed over and above the $38 billion
committed last year, and is examining the full range of options of
how to pay it off.
   The laundry list includes using interest on Federal Reserve funds
that is now paid into the general fund, or tapping the retained
earnings of the industry-owned regional Federal Home Loan Banks.
   Options in the reform package that will accompany any new money
include an administrative merger of the fund that insures commercial
banks with the S&amp;L fund, as well as additional control by federal
regulators over risky activities undertaken by state-chartered S&amp;Ls,
Parris said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890128-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 0132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AirlineCompetition     01-28 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airline Competition,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Above Average Air Fare Increases at Hub Airports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air fares since 1985 generally have increased
much faster than average at airports largely controlled by single
airlines, according to a new government study of those hub
operations.
   ``The present situation at hub airports is intolerable,'' Sen.
John Danforth, R-Mo., said Friday in releasing the study prepared by
the Transportation Department.
   He blamed the increases on a lack of competition at some airports
in the wake of deregulation of the airline industry in the 1970s.
   Under deregulation, most airlines have adopted ``hub and spoke''
operations to help lower their costs. The concept involves having
flights from smaller airports feed into a central airport, or hub,
where passengers make connections for their ultimate destinations.
   The study found that air fares rose substantially above national
averages from 1985 to 1988 at more than a half-dozen hub airports
dominated by single airlines: St. Louis; Charlotte, N.C.;
Cincinnati; Detroit; Minneapolis; Raleigh, N.C.; and Salt Lake City.
   The increases, in most instances, were twice or nearly three
times greater than the air fare portion of the Consumer Price Index
during the same period. The study looked at average round-trip
ticket prices for passengers beginning or ending their flights at
the hubs.
   Fares rose an average of 11.1 percent across the nation from 1985
to 1988, the study said. It said fares for the biggest carriers at
two major airports either rose less than the national average or
dropped over the three-year period.
   From 1985 to 1988, according to the study:
   _Piedmont Airlines fares rose 34 percent over three years at
Charlotte, where the airline had 89 percent of the market last year.
   _Delta Air Lines fares rose 25 percent at Cincinnati, where the
company had 81 percent of the market.
   _Northwest Airlines fares rose 27 percent at Detroit, where the
airline had 62 percent of the market.
   _Northwest fares rose 21 percent at Minneapolis, where the
airline had 77 percent of the market.
   _American Airlines fares rose 35 percent at Raleigh, where the
airline had 67 percent of the market.
   _Delta fares rose 26 percent at Salt Lake City. The airline had
77 percent of the market.
   _Delta fares rose 5 percent at Atlanta, where the airline
controls 62 percent of the market.
   _USAir fares dropped 6 percent at Pittsburgh, where the airline
had 80 percent of the market.
   The study focused, however, on Lambert-St. Louis International
Airport and the effects of a 1986 merger that made Trans World
Airlines the dominant carrier of passengers in and out of the city.
   Don Morrison, a TWA spokesman in St. Louis, disagreed with
Danforth's reading of the report. He said the study did not link the
increases to the airline's control of the market at its St. Louis
hub.
   The DOT study found that TWA fares at Lambert for non-stop
roundtrip travel increased 22.7 percent from the first half of 1985
to the first half of 1988. The airline component of the CPI rose
11.1 percent during the same period.
   ``I don't there is any correlation between the fare increases and
the hub operation,'' said Morrison. He attributed the increases to
``market forces.''
   The report did not examine in detail the other airports. It cited
the fares at other concentrated hubs only to show that TWA's air
fares had not increased faster than comparable airports across the
nation.
   However, the study cautioned, ``Hub concentration alone does not
explain why fares change or how much they change.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
