<FIRST>r w BC-Bush-Glance     01-28 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bush-Glance,570</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here at a glance are highlights from President
Bush's first formal news conference Friday:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>S&amp;L PROBLEMS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush said he was not disturbed by the flap in response to reports
that he was considering a fee that would be charged to S&amp;L
depositors to raise money for government efforts to deal with failed
institutions. ``It doesn't bother me for a lot of ideas to be
considered and debated. ... I have not made decisions on this one.
I'll wait till I get all the facts, call them as I see them, and
hope that we can convince the American people that that's the way to
go.'' He added: ``I will say this, that the savings and loans'
deposits are backed by the full faith and credit of the government.
And they are sound. They are good _ dollar good. And I just want to
assure the American people of that. And nothing is going to change
in that regard.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>CONGRESSIONAL PAY RAISE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush said of the Reagan-proposed $45,000 pay raise for judges,
members of Congress and other high-ranking government officials: ``I
do support it. A raise is overdue, there's no question about that.''
He added, ``I am troubled by certain aspects of the proposal ... but
we're down to the crunch here. The recommendation's up there on the
Hill _ it's either yea or nay. ... Seeing the problems as I do, I
still feel I should not go about undoing the Reagan decision.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>TRIP TO CHINA</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Asked about visiting China before responding to Soviet Leader
Mikhail Gorbachev's request for an early meeting, Bush replied: ``I
don't know what signal it sends in that regard, but let me just
remind you that I'm the one who does not believe in, quote, `playing
the Soviet card' or, quote, `playing the China card.' ... It just
seemed like an appropriate visit, but not to signal a playing of the
card to go one up on Mr. Gorbachev. There's nothing of that nature
in this visit. ... The visit stands on its own and does not have any
signaling that should be detrimental to anybody else's interest.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>MINIMUM WAGE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush reiterated his position that any increase in the minimum
wage should be ``linked to a training wage, to a differential of
sorts, so that you don't throw people out of work by raising the
minimum wage. And I'm not one who has felt that the minimum wage is
the key to economic prosperity for the lowest _ people on the lowest
end of the economic spectrum. But, as I indicated, a certain
flexibility on that question. And again, I'll wait for (Labor
Secretary) Elizabeth Dole, who takes office in the next couple of
days, to come in with her recommendations.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>THE PLO</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush said meetings would be held with the PLO ``as long as they
stay hooked and stay committed'' to accepting Israel's right to
exist, renouncing terrorism and accepting two U.N. resolutions
affirming the right of all Middle Eastern states to live within
secure borders. ``If there's some logical step that requires
high-level sign-off by various participants over there, then, and
then only, would it be proper to elevate the meetings to that level.
We're just starting. You crawl before you walk. We're just starting
to talk to them, because they have _ dramatically, I'd say _ agreed
to the, to the principles that are part of our policy.''
</TEXT>
