<FIRST>r i PM-Malaysia-Turtles     01-28 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Malaysia-Turtles,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giant Leatherback Turtles Of Malysia Becoming Extinct</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The giant leatherback turtles of
Malaysia are nearing extinction, with only 40 nesting last year at
Rantau Abang on the South China Sea, down from 1,800 in the 1950s,
an official said today.
   ``In the near future, the sea turtles of Malaysia may only be
alive in pictures,'' warned Khir Johari, president of the World
Wildlife Fund's Malaysia office.
   ``This represents an incredible 98 percent decline over 30 years.
Indeed, if nothing is done to help save this magnificent creature, I
can safely predict that within the next few years, the giant
leatherback turtle will be an extinct species, at least in
Malaysia,'' he added.
   Khir said the wildlife fund of Malaysia, in cooperation with the
Trengganu state government and Fisheries Department, will launch a
``save the sea turtles'' conservation program in March that includes
a turtle sanctuary in Rantau Abang, 180 miles to the northeast.
</TEXT>
