<DOCNO> AP890128-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 0152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Pakistan     01-28 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Pakistan,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Can't Be Sure Pakistan Doesn't Have Atomic Weapon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan is so close to building a nuclear bomb
that the United States probably won't be able to certify this year
that the country doesn't have one, the Reagan administration
reportedly told members of Congress before the former president left
office.
   That certification is necessary if Pakistan is to receive U.S.
economic and military aid beyond the current fiscal year. The Reagan
administration had requested $621 million in aid to Pakistan for
fiscal 1990, as part of a $4.02 billion, six-year package.
   The Washington Post today quoted congressional sources as saying
they were told by Reagan administration officials that Pakistan was
so close to building a bomb that ``it had been a very close call''
when the administration in November renewed the certification that
the country does not have a nuclear bomb.
   The newspaper said that when the certification was renewed, a
letter was attached to House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, saying the
administration was nearing its limits of being able to continue
making the certification.
   ``The Congress should be aware that as Pakistan's capabilities
grow, and if evidence about its activities continue to accumulate,
this process of annual certification will require the president to
reach judgments about the status of Pakistani nuclear activities
that may be difficult or impossible to make with any degree of
certainty,'' the Post quoted Reagan as saying.
   Without certification, required annually under the law, Pakistan
will not be eligible to receive U.S. economic and military aid
beyond the current fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30.
   The newspaper said it was not known if President Bush will accept
his predecessor's conclusion about Pakistan's nuclear capabilities,
although Bush is known to be extremely concerned about the problem
of nuclear weapons proliferation.
   In his letter to Wright, the Post said, Reagan said he had made
his ``best judgment'' on the basis of available information to the
U.S. government, based on the standard set by Congress regarding the
Pakistani nuclear program.
   The standard, he said, ``is whether Pakistan possesses a nuclear
explosive device, not whether Pakistan is attempting to develop or
has developed various relevant capacities.''
   Reagan said in the letter that the United States remained
``extremely troubled'' by the continuing risk of a nuclear arms race
between Pakistan and India, the Post said.
</TEXT>
