<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 0159EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Bush     01-28 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Bush,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Bush Comes to China as an `Old Friend'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush visits China next month as an old
friend of China's top leaders who has helped the nations weather
some of their stormiest relations.
   Bush will be in Beijing for two days after the Feb. 24 funeral in
Tokyo of Japan's Emperor Hirohito.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, in announcing the trip
Thursday in Washington, said Bush's close ties with China were an
element in the decision to visit Beijing just one month after taking
office.
   ``Undoubtedly there are some personal issues involved there in
terms of his relations with Deng Xiaoping,'' Fitzwater said, adding
that Bush will show support for Deng's economic reforms.
   Bush has known Deng, China's senior leader, since he headed the
U.S. Liaison Office in Beijing in 1974-75. Deng at the time was vice
premier but was soon to be purged by leftists in the dying days of
the disastrous 1966-76 Cultural Revolution.
   Deng was firmly in control when Bush, a candidate for vice
president, returned in 1980, a year after the United States and
China established diplomatic relations. Bush, Deng said, was a ``lao
pengyou,'' an ``old friend'' of the Chinese people.
   But his welcome was less than cordial. The Chinese were outraged
by statements by candidate Ronald Reagan that his administration
might restore official ties with Taiwan, and Bush was delegated to
convince the Chinese that there would be no backsliding in
U.S.-Chinese relations.
   ``Since we are old friends we must be very frank,'' Deng told
Bush. The official Xinhua News Agency later said Bush had ``failed
to reassure China over recent statements by Ronald Reagan.''
   But the visit also had its warmer moments. Bush and his wife,
Barbara, went shopping for teacups at the Friendship Store, the
special store for foreigners, and walked over to the International
Club. There, Bush renewed acquaintances with the barber, the manager
and the tennis court attendants he had known in 1974-75.
   Bush returned as vice president in May 1982, and told
then-premier and current Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang, ``We
feel at home in Beijing. During our stay here we spent a great deal
of time on our bicycles touring the city. ... Those were happy days.
Those were good days, important days.''
   That visit, however, also was dominated by the Taiwan question.
Deng spoke of the ``dark clouds'' of bilateral relations caused by
U.S. arms sales to Taiwan, and Bush's mission was to defuse
Beijing's demand for a final date by which all arms sales to the
rival Nationalists on Taiwan would cease.
   At the beginning of his official talks with Deng, Bush asked for
a five-minute private meeting. Instead, the two spent two hours
together and emerged to tell waiting aides that there was no need
for further discussions.
   Three months later the sides signed a communique in which
Washington agreed to gradually reduce arms sales to Taiwan.
   Bush's last visit in 1985 was decidedly more relaxed. He spoke to
students in Sichuan, took a boat ride down the scenic Li River in
Guilin and toured the prosperous southern cities of Canton and
Shenzhen. He also played tennis with then-Vice Premier Wan Li.
   ``I like what I see,'' Bush told Deng. ``We still have
fundamental differences, systematic differences with China. But
we're finding more and more things in common.''
   Chinese leaders, in a nation where personal ties often outweigh
ideological concerns, unabashedly favored Bush in the presidential
election and believe that the new administration will have better
understanding of and sympathy for China because of Bush's many
contacts here.
   Deng, in a meeting with Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci in
September, startled U.S. officials by saying he hoped China's ``old
friend'' Bush would win the election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890128-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 0202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Afghan-Academic     01-28 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghan-Academic,0764</SECOND>
<HEAD>Academic Freedom Stirs Faintly in the Cradle of a Marxist Revolution</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the Soviets head home, a faint wind
of change is stirring at Kabul University, cradle of the Afghan
intelligentsia whose Marxist revolution this impoverished Moslem
country has rejected.
   At the semester that started last fall, a majority of academic
staff voted for the science and agriculture faculties to scrap
courses in Marxist-style ideology that have been compulsory for all
the 7,000 students since the 1978 revolution.
   Hard-line members of the governing People's Democratic Party of
Afghanistan still hold key academic positions at the university,
which numbers among its graduates of the early 1970s Afghan
President Najib, a physician, and a dozen of his top political
associates.
   But for the first time since the revolution, deans who are not
party members _ five out of 13, according to the new engineering
dean _ were appointed last fall.
   Also, the U.S.-sponsored faculty of engineering is to reopen in
March at the end of the current extended winter vacation. It was
closed after Soviet troops arrived in Afghanistan in December 1979
to try to quell the rebellion.
   In a desolate building which houses the faculty, the laboratories
are stripped of most equipment and text books are more than a decade
out of date. The most talented lecturers long ago went into exile.
   At the entrance, two holes in plaster remain where
revolutionaries ripped down a plaque stating the faculty was a gift
from the United States.
   For five years until 1963, the faculty was linked to the
University of Wyoming and then sponsored jointly by 11 American
universities and technology institutes.
   ``Because the Soviet presence was so strong here, they (the
Afghan regime) wanted to pretend to them that anything that was not
Soviet-related was bad,'' said Ata Mohammad Nazar, the new dean of
the faculty.
   Nazar, 45, has a master's degree and doctorate in civil
engineering from Colorado State University and earns the equivalent
of $250 a month.
   Huddled over a single heater in a bone-chilling office, Nazar
nurtures a folorn hope: that U.S. universities will resume support
of the faculty even though Najib remains shakily in power as the
Soviets depart.
   The Soviets are due to leave by Feb. 15 under a U.N.-mandated
agreement signed in Geneva.
   But there is no sign of peace, with Moslem rebels still fighting
Najib's regime. Western countries are withholding aid and refuse to
deal with a regime they believe will fall after its Soviet
protectors depart.
   The engineering faculty, the only one that taught in English
before the revolution, plans to resume teaching in English.
   With educational standards plummeting through years of war and
Russian more widely taught than English, Nazar faces a tough task.
   He complained that Western countries, which cut ties with the
university in 1978, now punish the wrong people.
   ``We feel isolated,'' he said. ``The Russians say they made a
mistake coming here, so why should we take the blame?''
   ``To remove this government and install another: is it worth it?
They will defend themselves. How many more Afghans should die?'' he
added.
   In a nearby administrative building, Dr. Mohammad Khamrani, 35, a
founding party member who has the title of vice chancellor for
social and cultural affairs at the university, has a blunt answer.
   ``It may take millions of lives,'' he said of the conflict in
which about 1 million people already have died. ``But I am certain
we will not collapse ... The system will survive.''
   He said the scaling down of political courses as more of an
administrative arrangement to accommodate extra numbers of
non-science students in the programs.
   Khamrani, a neurologist who graduated a few years behind Najib,
spoke with scarcely concealed impatience of ``barefoot peasants''
steeped in Islam, whom the revolution was to liberate.
   The West ``rudely interfered in our affairs,'' he charged. But
Khamrani added that he and his fellow revolutionaries made some
mistakes too, trying to change things too fast in a ``feudal,
agrarian and backward society.''
   Despite rebels operating within a few miles of the city and the
Soviets on their way out, he appeared not to contemplate possible
death or jail for being a high profile party member.
   ``The Soviets will help us,'' he said from his seat beneath a
portrait of Najib. ``They won't leave us alone.''
</TEXT>
