<DOCNO> AP890128-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 0203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Vietnam-TherapyTrip     01-28 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-Therapy Trip,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight U.S. Vets Return To Vietnam As Treatment For Traumatic Stress</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE ESPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dave Roberts has trouble sleeping at
night. He dreams he is back in Vietnam more than 20 years ago going
down a dark river on a Navy patrol boat trying to ambush Viet Cong
soldiers.
   He is 19 years old and scared, having been wounded once already.
Startled, he awakens in his bedroom in Tacoma, Wash.
   Roberts, now 40, and seven other veterans from the Seattle-Tacoma
area are returning to Vietnam to revisit their bases and relive
their war days of two decades ago as treatment for post-traumatic
stress disorder, which includes sleeplessness and restlessness.
   ``I want to come to peace with my mind, the country and the
people and put all that behind me because the war's over,'' Roberts
said Friday during a stopover in Bangkok en route to Hanoi on the
first leg of the group's two-week tour. ``I want to get on with a
lot of things in my life.''
   Another veteran, Bob Swanson, 39, a Marine who helped build U.S.
fire bases, wants to rid himself of guilt.
   ``There's apologies I feel I need to make to the people,'' said
Swanson. ``There were civilians who were caught in our fire, and
I've had guilt feelings about that. The other thing is to try to
leave the warrior part of me in Vietnam where it belongs. It doesn't
fit in the United States.''
   Accompanying the veterans are two therapists, Ray Scurfield, a
Vietnam veteran himself, and April Gerlock, and a film crew that
will make a documentary that could be used in therapy for other
veterans.
   The veterans will undergo therapy during the trip and for two
months after they return home. They had been required to attend
group therapy sessions once a week for the last five months in
preparation for their return to Vietnam.
   ``Basically we're utilizing sort of an extension of a very
accepted therapeutic practice in working with trauma survivors,''
said Scurfield, director of the PTSD program at the American Lake
Veterans Hospital near Tacoma. ``That is direct therapeutic exposure
to the trauma.''
   ``By coming over here, our assumption is it will trigger
repressed memories and feelings that they they need to get out
consciously and talk about,'' he said. ``In doing that it appears
they come to some kind of a peace.''
   Scurfield said many veterans picture Vietnam today as it was 20
years ago.
   ``By going now,'' he said, ``they have to substitute the reality
of Vietnam today. It's not the way it was 20 years ago. That's a
very important message for many veterans.''
   The veterans will see a new landscape devoid of U.S. artillery
and air bases, covered over by red dirt, with few reminders of the
more than half a million American troops who served there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890128-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 0204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0421 01-28 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0421,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial to Start Next Week; Subpoena Issue to be Resolved Monday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``I guess...'' to remove extra first
reference to Gesell; SUBS 10th graf pvs, bgng: ``Gesell delayed...'' to
CORRECT spelling of Saltzberg; picks up 11th graf pvs, bgng: ``Meanwhile,
an...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell asserted his
authority to compel testimony from President Bush or former
President Reagan, and plans to rule Monday on whether to throw out
subpoenas for the two in the trial of fired White House aide Oliver
North.
   The trial of North in the Iran-Contra case was still scheduled to
begin Tuesday after an interagency task force of intelligence
experts concluded that classified documents to be presented in the
case don't pose a serious national security risk.
   ``I guess we're ready to go,'' Gesell told lawyers for both sides
Friday. ``I'll see all of you at 9:30 Tuesday morning.''
   At a hearing, Gesell said that judicial authority to force Bush
or Reagan to testify is ``indisputable.''
   ``As far as the power of the court to require testimony'' of
Reagan or Bush is concerned, ``I do not think there is any
question,'' he said. ``The court has the power.''
   Justice Department official Stephen Saltzberg said that North's
subpoenas should be quashed because the former National Security
Council aide had not specified how Bush's and Reagan's testimony
would be relevant at trial.
   Gesell said he envisioned having the Reagan subpoena remain in
force, with Reagan ``on call'' but under no obligation to appear
immediately, and the government would be heard again before any
order for him to appear.
   Larry Simms, one of Reagan's lawyers, was in the courtroom for
the hearing. Former Justice Department official Theodore Olson is
the lead attorney representing the former president.
   North also is seeking presidential documents, including Reagan's
diary. John Keker, the lawyer who will prosecute North, said that
the White House counsel a year ago had prepared typed excerpts from
the diary. Lawyers from the office of independent counsel Lawrence
Walsh, for whom Keker works, reviewed the excerpts, but did not get
copies of them, said Keker.
   Gesell delayed a ruling on the documents subpoena. Saltzberg is
to contact Reagan's lawyers and make arrangements to have those
diary segments made available to North's lawyers as well.
   Meanwhile, an administration official said secrecy concerns would
not block North's trial.
   The interagency group of intelligence experts had identified some
documents that might pose problems if Gesell allowed their
disclosure in open court by North's lawyers.
   However, much would depend on Gesell's rulings from the bench
during the trial on the relevancy and admissibility of the
documents, said the administration official, speaking on condition
of anonymity. And he said government secrecy experts familiar with
the documents did not expect the sensitive material to be admitted
because it didn't appear relevant to the case.
   The official said administration officials planned to monitor the
trial closely in the event there was an attempt by North's lawyers
to introduce into evidence documents that would compromise national
security.
   Another government source close to the matter, also speaking on
condition of anonymity, said that one agency he declined to identify
had problems with some of the classified information in the case,
but that the other agencies represented on the intelligence task
force had refused to go along with the objections.
   North is accused of concealing from Congress and from former
Attorney General Edwin Meese III his efforts on behalf of the
Nicaraguan Contras and of covering up the NSC's role in diverting
money from the Iran arms sales to the Contras.
   North also is accused of illegally accepting a $13,800 security
system at his home from co-defendant Richard Secord, converting to
his own use at least $4,300 in traveler's checks from Contra leader
Adolfo Calero and conspiring to defraud the Treasury of tax revenue
in connection with charitable contributions supporting the Contras.
</TEXT>
