<FIRST>r w PM-UnionMembership     01-28 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Union Membership,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Rolls Steady; Percentage Of Work Force in Unions Drops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor unions represented a slightly smaller
share of the nation's work force in 1988 even though the total
number of union members increased, the government reports.
   The Labor Department reported Friday that the number of Americans
belonging to labor unions rose by 100,000 to 17 million last year,
but the size of the overall work force increased even faster.
   Union members continued last year to earn more than non-union
workers. Full-time workers who were union members had median weekly
earnings of $480 compared with $356 for those who were not union
members, the department reported.
   The department said 16.8 percent of the 101 million wage and
salary employees in the United States last year were union members,
down from 17 percent in 1987 and 18 percent in 1985.
   The 100,000 new union members came from the ranks of black
workers, the Labor Department said.
   In fact, there were slight decreases in the number of whites and
Hispanics belonging to unions last year. Membership among black
workers rose from 2.44 million in 1987 to 2.55 million last year,
the Labor Department said.
   The membership gain, although slight, provided some solace to
union officials who have dedicated many of their efforts in recent
years to trying to reverse declining membership.
   ``We hope we have bottomed out, but we don't know yet for sure,''
said Rex Hardesty, a spokesman for the AFL-CIO.
   There were 10.7 union members in private industry last year and
6.3 million government workers in unions.
</TEXT>
