<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua     01-28 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Proposes Referendum On Constitutional Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>By RODOLFO GARCIA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition coalition has proposed
elections for Nicaraguans to decide if they want major
constitutional reforms, the newspaper La Prensa reported.
   The opposition newspaper said the president of the Nicaraguan
Democratic Coordinate, Carlos Huembes, signed the proposal, which
was sent to President Daniel Ortega on Friday.
   La Prensa said constitutional reforms sought by the opposition
group included free elections, democratic reforms and amnesty for
political prisoners.
   The referendum would ask ``if the government should ... accept
the constitutional reforms, considering the urgency of the
circumstances.''
   Ortega is scheduled to make ``transcendent announcements'' about
the country's economic policies today when he meets with leaders of
union, peasant and professional groups that support the ruling
Sandinista government, pro-government news media reported.
   Economic conditions in Nicaragua are deteriorating and shortages
of food and basic commodities are common.
   The leftist Sandinista government and the opposition deadlocked a
year ago on discussions of such proposed constitutional reforms.
   ``We hope that the government ... will see it is obligated to
soon make announcements about the policies that affect the social
base of all Nicaraguans,'' La Prensa quoted the letter as saying.
   The opposition group is formed by five opposition political
parties, two unions and a group of professionals.
   The opposition group said it hoped that a peace summit of Central
American presidents, canceled earlier this month, will be
rescheduled for Feb. 13-14.
   The summit was canceled after Costa Rican President Oscar Arias
asked for more time for President Bush to formulate his policy in
the region.
   Although various proposals have been made, no new date has been
set.
   Ortega, Arias and the presidents of Guatemala, El Salvador and
Honduras were to resume stalled talks on a stalled Central American
peace plan.
   The August 1987 plan that Arias designed calls for an end to
civil wars in Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala, political
amensties and democratic guarantees in the five Central American
nations.
   The Sandinista government and U.S.-backed anti-communist rebels
agreed in March 1988 to suspend offensive operations, but talks
aimed at a permanent end to the 7-year war are at an impasse.
</TEXT>
