<FIRST>r i PM-Dominican-Crash     01-28 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dominican-Crash,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>23 Haitian Workers Killed In Truck Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck carrying Haitian
sugar cane workers missed a curve on a cliff, overturned and plunged
into a ravine, killing at least 23 people and injuring 40,
authorities said.
   Military officials said the truck was traveling Friday to Santo
Domingo with about 78 Haitians who had been recruited for the annual
sugar harvest when it crashed in about 22 miles north of the
capital. The Dominican Republic shares the island of Hispaniola with
Haiti.
   The injured, including five children and three women, were taken
to Santo Domingo hospitals for treatment. Doctors said at least 13
people were listed in serious condition.
   Julio Guerrero, spokesman for the State Sugar Council which
operates 12 of the country's 16 mills, said the council was not
responsible for transporting the Haitians.
   Dominicans recruit Haitians at low wages for the tortuous work of
cutting sugar cane.
</TEXT>
