<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 0353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Pakistan-Elections     01-28 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Elections,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>By-Elections Battle Between Bhutto And Her Rivals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three million voters went to the polls
today in elections to fill 20 seats of the National Assembly and
provincial legislatures.
   The elections commission announced one of the seats for the
National Assembly, the lower house of Pakistan's parliament, had
been won because it was uncontested by a member of Prime Minister
Benazir Bhutto's Pakistan Peoples Party.
   At stake are 13 seats in 237-member National Assembly and seven
in three of Pakistan's four provincial legislatures.
   The polls are taking place in districts where candidates in last
November's general elections won more than one seat, or the vote was
postponed because a candidate died.
   The outcome of the polls cannot dent the position of Ms. Bhutto,
who heads the federal government in Islamabad on the basis of her
sizeable majority, bolstered by support from smaller groups and
independent lawmakers.
   At the center of the opposition is Ghulam Mustafa Jatoi, chairman
of 9-party Islamic Democratic Alliance, a rival of Ms. Bhutto's. He
is contesting for the national assembly from the rural Kot Addu
district of Punjab, the nation's biggest and richest province where
the democratic alliance rules.
   The by-election results will indicate whether the Pakisan
People's Party or the Islamic Democratic Alliance has lost or gained
in popularity since November's general elections.
   Polls opened at 8 a.m. and close at 5 p.m. Results were expected
Sunday.
</TEXT>
