<FIRST>r a PM-McNamaraLetter     01-28 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McNamara Letter,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Demand McNamara Be Fired</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis has joined the
growing ranks of prosecutors and political leaders calling for the
resignation of U.S. Attorney Frank L. McNamara, who is under fire
for a variety of alleged improprieties.
   ``The situation has been an embarrassment for months and months
and months,'' Dukakis said Friday. ``I don't think this appointment
should ever have been made.''
   Twenty-eight of the 39 federal prosecutors in Massachussetts
called for the removal or resignation of McNamara, who is their
boss, saying his presence is jeopardizing the credibility of their
office.
   Criticism of McNamara, a 41-year-old Republican appointed by
President Reagan in 1987, has been growing since November, when the
Justice Department said it could find no basis for his allegations
that his predecessor, William F. Weld, smoked marijuana at a party.
   Shortly thereafter, McNamara admitted that he had smoked
marijuana as recently as four years ago. More recently, he has been
criticized for pressing investigations that were allegedly aimed at
discrediting Democrats, including Dukakis.
   McNamara declined comment Friday. Asked how he could continue his
duties under the circumstances, he replied, ``You have to address
that question to somebody else, because I don't have any comment.''
   Prosecutors in the Boston and Springfield offices under
McNamara's command sent a letter Friday to U.S. Attorney General
Richard Thornburgh urging him to fire the embattled chief prosecutor.
   ``Because Mr. McNamara will neither resign nor step aside
temporarily, the credibility and operations of this office will
continue to be damaged, perhaps irretrievably, unless he is
removed,'' the letter said.
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., said if no action is forthcoming from
the Justice Department, ``then I think (congressional) hearings will
be necessary.''
</TEXT>
