<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionProtests     01-28 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Protests,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Guilty Of Trespass In Abortion Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some anti-abortion protesters convicted on charges
stemming from last summer's demonstrations say they will not pay
their $500 fines, the leader of an anti-abortion group said.
   Nine men were convicted Friday in Fulton County State Court of
criminal trespassing and unlawful assembly for blocking entrances
and driveways at the Feminist Women's Health Center on Aug. 10.
   The nine were fined $500 each and given six months probation.
   But Michael Hirsh, local director of the New York-based
anti-abortion organization Operation Rescue, met with the men after
the trial and said later that several planned to refuse to pay the
fine.
   ``We will go toe-to-toe with the system at every opportunity and
we'll continue to until they lay us in our graves and outlaw
abortion,'' Hirsh said.
   The jury deliberated about 20 minutes after hearing two days of
testimony in the case, which stemmed from a series of demonstrations
organized in Atlanta by Operation Rescue that landed more than 1,000
protesters in jail.
   Lynn Wilson, vice president of the Georgia Abortion Rights Action
League, said the convictions set an important precedent.
   ``It's important as a symbol,'' Ms. Wilson said. ``I think it's
clear now that the public is not, and will not, be willing to accept
Operation Rescue and its illegal tactics.''
</TEXT>
