<DOCNO> AP890128-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 0450EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Argentina     01-28 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Warns Of Further Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several armed civilians who took
over an suburban army base escaped a military counterattack and may
be preparing another assault, Argentina's attorney general says.
   ``We know that in this attack more people participated than were
killed or arrested,'' Andres D'Alessio told a news conference Friday.
   D'Alessio said a former leader of the now-defunct People's
Revolutionary Army, Enrique Gorriaran Merlo, took part in the
attack, but offered no proof of his involvement.
   ``His participation is presumed, taking into account his former
guerrilla activity, his training and the connection he had in recent
times with (leftist groups),'' D'Alessio said.
   The government says 60 leftist guerrillas staged the assault. The
armed civilians battled soldiers for 27 hours, and 38 people died,
including 28 guerrillas. Eighteen of the attackers were captured.
   D'Alessio said police have interrogated the survivors and jailed
two more people. He said arrest warrants have been issued for five
others, including Gorriaran Merlo. He said more violence was
possible.
   ``An armed group that suffers a public defeat of this size in
general sees it as necessary to do something to demonstrate it's
still in condition to keep operating,'' he said.
   The People's Revolutionary Army clashed openly with Argentina's
army in the 1970s in an attempt to overthrow the government. The
guerrilla army was thought to be virtually decimated. It had
formally disbanded in 1980.
   Gorriaran Merlo fled to Nicaragua. According to police reports
and his own admission in a published interview, he participated in
the 1980 bazooka attack on a street in Asuncion, Paraguay, that
killed deposed Nicaraguan dictator Anastasio Somoza.
   Gorriaran Merlo, 47, has been wanted by Argentine police for
years. President Raul Alfonsin ordered his prosecution shortly after
taking office in December 1983.
</TEXT>
