<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 0515EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     01-28 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Piles Up In the Rockies, Thunderstorms Boom In Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow piled up in the southern Rockies today in a storm that
triggered tractor-trailer wrecks in Colorado, and scattered showers
and thunderstorms extended over the central and southern Plains.
   Clear skies prevailed over much of the nation.
   The Western storm left 8 inches of snow in Durango, Colo., and
Farmington, N.M., and 7 inches in Jemez Mountains northwest of Santa
Fe, N.M., on Friday. Denver and Colorado Springs, Colo., had light
snow.
   Winds gusted to 50 mph in the Colorado Springs area, and Pueblo,
Colo., had dense fog.
   Several tractor-trailer rigs jackknifed and there were a couple
of auto accidents on Interstate 25 in Colorado, but no serious
injuries were reported, said State Patrol communications officer
Donald Piquette. The interstate was temporarily closed because of
ice.
   A winter storm warning for heavy snow was in effect for the Four
Corners area of Colorado. Snow advisories were in effect for the
southern mountains of Colorado, the northern mountains of New Mexico
and the northwest Plains of New Mexico.
   Scattered thunderstorms fell across central and northwest Texas
today, and rain showers extended over central and northern Texas,
Oklahoma, central Kansas and south central Nebraksa. Dense fog
enveloped parts of Texas.
   Thunderstorms late Friday produced small hail near Andrews,
Texas, and at Hobbs, N.M.
   High-temperature records for Jan. 27 were broken Friday in seven
cities in the Midwest and Florida and tied in five. It was a balmy
60 degrees in Yankton, S.D., where the old record of 53 degrees was
set in 1909, and the 63-degree reading in Rapidy City, S.D., tied a
record set in 1896.
   The nation's high temperature Friday was 84 degrees in West
Kendall, Fla.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorm over much of
the southern and central Plains and western sections of the lower
and middle Mississippi Valley, with thunderstorms most numerous over
central and northeast Texas; snow over the Texas and Oklahoma
panhandles, eastern Colorado and northeast New Mexico; scattered
snow over northern Maine; and strong, gusty winds along the eastern
slopes of the Montana Rockies.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 50s and 60s from the
middle and south Atlantic Coast to the Ohio and Tennessee valleys,
the lower middle Mississippi Valley, the southern two-thirds of
Texas, the desert Southwest and much of California; the 70s in
extreme southern Texas and much of Florida; and in the 30s and 40s
elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 12
degrees below zero at Idaho Falls, Idaho, to 70 degrees at Key West,
Fla., and McAllen and Brownsville, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 39 fair; Boston 30 fair; Buffalo 31 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 48 fair; Cincinnati 30 fair; Cleveland 31 fair;
Detroit 29 fair; Miami 67 partly cloudy; New York 36 fair;
Philadelphia 30 fair; Pittsburgh 26 foggy; Portland, Maine 15 fair;
Washington 36 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 28 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 51 showers; Denver
35 snow; Des Moines 39 fair; Indianapolis 34 fair; Kansas City 39
fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 35 fair; Nashville 32 fair; New Orleans
55 fair; St. Louis 39 partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 33 cloudy; Anchorage -23 windy; Las Vegas 40
fair; Los Angeles 51 foggy; Phoenix 49 partly cloudy; Salt Lake City
9 hazy; San Diego 51 foggy; San Francisco 45 partly cloudy; Seattle
41 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 7 fair; Toronto 28 fair.
