<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Accident     01-28 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Accident,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Bodies Found In Ship Collision, Officer Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The coast guard today found two more bodies believed
to be crewmen of a freighter that collided with another vessel and
sank off western Japan, maritime officials said.
   The discovery brought to six the number of bodies recovered after
the 2,900-ton Catherine-Rose, a Panamanian-registered cargo ship
carrying 17 South Korean crew members, sank Thursday off
Yoshimi-cho, 530 miles west of Tokyo.
   The six had not yet been identified, said Yasushi Horie of the
Moji branch of the Maritime Safety Agency, Japan's coast guard.
   Six boats, two helicopters and a plane were searching the area
today, Horie said.
   On Friday night, police arrested a deck officer of the other ship
_ the 2,400-ton Semba Wang of Singapore _ in connection with the
collision, Horie said.
   Choi Young-kyo, 48, was the vessel's duty officer at the time of
the accident, Horie noted. He declined to elaborate.
   Officials said none of the 16 men on board the Semba Wang, all
South Koreans, were injured, but the ship sustained ``heavy'' damage
to its bow.
   The Catherine-Rose, bound for the South Korean port of Pusan, had
a cargo of 3,000 tons of scrap steel.
   The Samba Wang was traveling from Yosu on South Korea's
southwestern coast to Mizushima, Japan, 350 miles west of Tokyo,
officials said.
</TEXT>
