<FIRST>r a PM-MiamiRiot     01-28 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miami Riot,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conyers: Miami's Overtown Has Been Shortchanged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After touring the scene of Miami's recent riots, a
Michigan congressman accused police of being ``trigger-happy'' and
said he could sense the seeds of discontent among the area's black
residents.
   ``There's a lot of pent-up frustration in this (area), anger,
bitterness,'' Rep. John Conyers said Friday as he stood in front of
the charred ruins of a grocery store in the predominantly black
Overtown neighborhood.
   At another point he told a resident who was concerned about a
lack of jobs: ``Overtown has been shorted. The question is how did
it happen and what we can do.''
   Conyers, chairman of the Government Operations Committee and a
member of the Judiciary subcommittee on civil and constitutional
rights, promised to help coordinate relief for Overtown.
   The fatal shooting of a black motorcylist by a Hispanic police
officer on Jan. 16 sparked three days of burning, looting and
violence. The motorcyclist's passenger died of injuries sustained in
an ensuing wreck.
   The unrest spilled over into the Liberty City area, and left one
dead, 11 wounded by gunfire and about $1 million in structural
damage, not including the buildings' contents.
   Conyers, who was invited to tour the area by Raymond Fauntroy,
president of the local chapter of the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference, told cheering residents at a community meeting that
there are ``too many trigger-happy policemen abusing the rights of
black people in this area.''
   The Democrat also charged that federal funding the Carter
administration promised in the aftermath of riots in 1980 was later
cut by the Reagan administration.
   For example, he said, of $40 million in loans slated for small
business owners, only $16 million ever made it into the community.
Of $10 million for low-income housing, only $2 million came through
for Overtown, he said.
   ``It's part of the legacy of broken promises to Overtown,''
Conyers said.
</TEXT>
