<FIRST>r a PM-GiulianiPlot     01-28 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Giuliani Plot,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indictment Alleges Death Plot Against U.S. Attorney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted drug dealer has been arrested in
prison on charges of trying to arrange the killing of U.S. Attorney
Rudolph Giuliani.
   Salvatore Spatola allegedly plotted to kill Giuliani in a July 21
telephone call with an undercover New York City police detective.
Spatola was in prison at the time for an earlier drug conviction.
   Spatola, 40, and his brother, Federico, 45, of Scotch Plains,
N.J., were named in a racketeering indictment unsealed Friday.
   In addition to racketeering, both were charged in the 10-count
indictment with conspiracy, heroin trafficking and conspiring to
kill two people other than Giuliani in a murder-for-hire deal.
   Giuliani, who is scheduled to leave office next week, declined to
comment about the case.
   Salvatore Spatola was arrested Friday at the Federal Correctional
Institution in Lewisberg, Pa., where he is serving his five-year
sentence.
   Last October, Spatola pleaded guilty to state charges for his
part in the bungled 1987 rubout attempt on a defendant in the
massive Pizza Connection drug case.
   His brother was arrested at his Manhattan pizzeria. Prosecutors
sought to have him held without bail and U.S. Magistrate Nina
Gershon ordered him held pending a bail hearing Tuesday.
   In the racketeering counts, both brothers were accused of
plotting to distribute large quantities of heroin and also plotting
last year to have two people other than Giuliani killed.
</TEXT>
