<FIRST>u i PM-NorthernIreland-Bomb 1stLd-Writethru a0449 01-28 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland-Bomb, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0449,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Policeman Killed, Two Injured In Bomb Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with third policemen injured, other
details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb tossed at a passing
police car from the roof of a nearby building exploded today,
killing one policeman and injuring two others, officials said.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for the attack in the
border village of Sion Mills in west Northern Ireland, but suspicion
fell on the Irish Republican Army, which is fighting British rule in
the province.
   A spokesman at police headquarters in Belfast said the three
policemen were driving down the main street of the village when
someone standing in the doorway of a pub signaled for them to stop.
   Not realizing it was an ambush, the policemen halted their car
and one got out to investigate. An assailant then threw a bomb at
the car from the roof of a nearby building, wrecking the car, police
said.
   One of the two officers inside the vehicle died of his injuries
as he was being taken to a hospital, and the other officer inside
the car was badly hurt, police said.
   The third policeman was also slightly injured when about 200
people spilling out of a nearby discotheque pelted him with bottles
as he went to the aid of his colleagues, police said.
   A woman near the scene was treated for shock, police said.
   The noisy crowd also attacked army and police arriving at the
scene but was dispersed when the reinforcements fired a rubber
bullet, said the police spokesman, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland and unite it with the mostly
Catholic Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
