<FIRST>r a PM-MilitaryCrash     01-28 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Military Crash,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Killed in Crash of Navy Jet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARIZONA CITY, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Navy fliers were killed when their
F-14 jet fighter crashed in a cotton field while on a training
flight from California to Louisiana, a military spokesman said.
   The cause of the crash, which occurred Friday about six miles
west of Arizona City, was under investigation, said Petty Officer
Barbara Vega, a Navy spokeswoman in San Diego.
   The plane was assigned to squadron VF-114 at Miramar Naval Air
Station in San Diego, she said.
   Identities of the pilot and the radar-intercept officer were
withheld pending notification of relatives.
   ``It was really an unfortunate accident. This squadron had just
finished flying five years without an accident,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Bob
Pritchard, another Navy spokesman in San Diego.
   Pritchard said the jet and another F-14 left Miramar Friday on a
routine training flight. He said the second F-14 landed at
Davis-Monthan Air Force Base in Tucson and was to return to Miramar,
he said.
   There apparently was no communiciation with the second fighter or
air-traffic controllers before the crash, and it was not known
whether the victims tried to eject, Pritchard said.
   There were no other injuries at the crash scene and no buildings
were damaged, he added.
</TEXT>
