<FIRST>r a PM-EconomyRdp     01-28 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>GNP Growth Strong For 1988; Dollar Continues Its Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street cheered a government report that indicated the
nation's economy lost some of its steam in the fourth quarter of
1988, easing fears that the pace of economic growth could fuel
inflation.
   The Commerce Department reported Friday that the nation's gross
national product slowed to 2.0 percent in the fourth quarter. The
figure was below Wall Street's expectations and provided fresh
evidence that the economy was slowing to a sustainable pace.
   The report also said the economy grew a healthy 3.8 percent for
all of 1988.
   Bond traders welcomed the fourth-quarter growth figure by bidding
up prices of long-term government bonds _ thereby pushing interest
rates lower _ which provided fresh momentum for Wall Street's
ongoing rally.
   Brokers said a rise in the dollar in foreign-exchange trading
Friday also helped stir investors' enthusiasm for stocks.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks climbed 31.79
points to 2,322.86, bringing its gain for the week to 87.50 points.
   The government said the 1988 GNP figure benefited from a
narrowing of the trade deficit and a large increase in business
investment.
   The increase came even though growth slowed sharply in the final
three months of the year to the slowest quarterly performance in two
years.
   Commenting on the GNP report, the Bush administration said the
fourth-quarter slowdown was not a warning that the six-year record
peacetime economic recovery was in endangered and should not
overshadow the stellar performance of the economy for all of 1988.
   The GNP report also indicated inflation picked up during the
year, with a price index tied to the GNP rising by 4.2 percent, the
fastest increase since a 6.2 percent rise in 1982.
   Analysts said the Federal Reserve likely will consider the
inflation level too high and keep up its pressure on interest rates.
But Bush on Friday played down any differences between the
administration and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   ``He is more concerned about inflation pressures than I am right
now,'' Bush said at a news conference. ``It seems to me there is an
area of difference. But generally speaking, I think we are fairly
close together.''
</TEXT>
