<SECOND>PM-Michael Jackson,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Celebrities Rush To See Show Billed As Pop Idol's Last</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUINN LOTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Michael Jackson has apparently forsaken
the concert stage at age 30, giving what was billed as his last
performance.
   Jackson, appearing an hour late after being mobbed backstage by
celebrity well-wishers, took the stage Friday night amid a vapor
mist and the deafening roar of a capacity crowd at the Los Angeles
Sports Arena.
   ``Since this is the last concert there was a big mob scene
backstage,'' publicist Lee Solters said early today. ``A lot of
people were wishing him well.''
   Dozens of stretch limousines were on hand, carrying stars such as
actors Elizabeth Taylor, Jane Fonda, Raquel Welch and Michael Landon
and singers Phil Collins, Dionne Warwick, Tiffany and members of the
heavy metal group Motley Crue.
   Many fans said they had waited weeks to see Jackson, who canceled
December shows in Los Angeles because of strained vocal cords.
Tickets for the farewell show were fetching prices well beyond their
face value.
   Sylvia Smith, 35, who attended the concert with her 9-year-old
daughter, Barika, said she was offered $100 for her $27.50 loge seat
but turned it down.
   ``It was tempting since I could've let Barika go in with her aunt
and uncle,'' Ms. Smith said. ``But she said, `No Mommy, you gotta
go.' And I figured if it's Michael's last concert, I may as well be
part of history.''
   Although Friday's show was billed as a farewell performance,
Jackson's manager backed off from saying the reclusive performer
would never appear in concert again.
   ``I'm not saying he's not going to perform live again, but I
don't think we'll ever go out on tour like this,'' Frank Dileo said.
   The show marked the end of Jackson's ``Bad'' tour, a grueling,
16-month effort that took him around the world.
   Jackson, celebrated as widely for his eccentricities as for his
songs, vocals and choreography, intends to keep recording and is
considering film roles, Solters said.
   Jackson, who hasn't granted an interview since 1984, is said to
be interested in movies, writing, producing and directing.
   Taking the stage accompanied by bodyguards, Jackson sang and
danced his way through a number of his hits Friday night, backed by
dancers dressed as punk rockers, monsters and street gang members.
   He used his signature ``moonwalk'' movements to glide across
stage, singing such songs as ``Starting Something,'' ``The Way You
Make Me Feel'' and ``Man in the Mirror,'' as the audience howled and
stomped in approval.
</TEXT>
