<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 0712EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MouseGame     01-28 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mouse Game,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scurrying Rodents Barred From County Fair Contests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mouse game, as familiar to Maine
county fairgoers as Ferris wheels and cotton candy, is destined to
become a midway memory.
   Fair officials attending the annual meeting of the Maine
Association of Agricultural Fairs learned Friday that the mouse game
had been declared illegal _ just like the cow chip casino.
   In the mouse game, players buy numbered tickets in hopes that a
mouse, when released, will run down a correspondingly numbered hole
on the rim of a spinning table.
   The director of the state Animal Welfare Board, Clyde F. LeClair,
said any game of chance in which an animal is used to determine the
outcome is prohibited by statute. Horse racing is regulated by a
separate set of laws.
   The cow chip contest, in which a cow is turned loose in a
fenced-in area lined with numbered squares, became illegal in late
September when state police shut down a contest at the Cumberland
Fair. The proceeds were to help buy playground equipment at a local
school.
   The head of the licensing division, Sgt. Bruce Refnell, confirmed
that until the Cumberland Fair incident, he was unaware of the state
humane law prohibiting the use of animals.
   ``That got us thinking about the mice used at the fairs, and they
fall under the same rule,'' Refnell said
   Billy Burr of Billy Burr's Fun-O-Rama said his midways did not
use the mouse game last year.
   ``In fact, Maine was the only state that I know of that still
allowed the game,'' Burr said Friday. ``It's another tradition lost
but it won't affect me at all.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
