<FIRST>r a PM-TeamstersMeeting     01-28 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teamsters Meeting,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Union Leaders Meeting To Discuss Government's Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters union leaders have been called to a
meeting in Washington today to discuss the federal government's
offer to settle a racketeering lawsuit, a newspaper reported.
   The Plain Dealer of Cleveland said the union's 16 international
vice presidents were notified Friday of the meeting in a message
from union President William J. McCarthy.
   The message said the meeting was to discuss ``pending
litigation'' and invited the vice presidents to bring their lawyers,
the newspaper said in today's editions.
   The meeting was called after U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani of
New York reportedly sent an 18-page settlement proposal to Teamsters
general counsel James T. Grady.
   Giuliani is leaving office next week and was described by one
Teamsters associate as eager to settle the lawsuit he filed against
the union in federal court last June, the Plain Dealer said. The
suit, which seeks the removal of top officers of the 1.6
million-member union, is scheduled for trial Feb. 27.
   The newspaper, citing unidentified sources, said the proposed
settlement calls for direct election of the union's president,
secretary-treasurer and international vice presidents. An
independent panel would oversee the elections and monitor union
activities.
   Teamsters have been electing leaders through delegates at
conventions every five years.
</TEXT>
