<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Privacy     01-28 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Privacy,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill To Tame Tabloids Dies in Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House of Commons scuttled legislation intended
to protect individuals from intrusive newspaper reporting when the
bill's supporters failed to muster enough support to force a vote.
   Even some legislators whose private lives had become grist for
London's racier dailies spoke against the bill on Friday, and the
government said remedies already existed.
   The bill's sponsor, Conservative John Browne, said, ``Preserving
privacy is in the public interest. We hope this bill will put water
in the moat of everyone's castle.''
   After five hours of debate Friday, the bill fell one short of the
necessary 100 votes to close debate and vote on whether it should
move to the next parliamentary phase _ called a second reading. The
House of Commons has 650 members.
   The legislation would have created a statutory right of privacy
and permitted suits for breaches. It would have placed the burden on
the newspaper to show that its disclosures were for the public
benefit.
   George Galloway, a Labor Party member, said he and his family had
been subjected to what he called the ``rampaging rat packs of the
tabloid press'' following his admission in 1987 that he had had an
extramarital affair. But he still opposed the measure.
   Timothy Renton, minister of state in the Home Office, told
legislators there was growing resentment ``at the way some of the
tabloid press blatantly exposes private lives.''
   However, Renton said the bill in question could prove ``a clumsy
instrument.''
   Robin Corbett, a Labor member who once worked for the tabloid
Daily Mirror, denounced the government's apparent neutrality on the
issue.
   ``There is no doubt at all that the excesses of the sewer Sun and
other tabloids have reached such proportions in the quest for
sensation and sleaze that action must be now taken,'' Corbett said.
   Britain's tabloids far outsell such respected newspapers as The
Daily Telegraph or The Times. The Sun, with circulation of 4.2
million, is read by a quarter of all adults in Britain, according to
readership surveys made in 1986. The tabloid Daily Mirror reached 20
percent of adults, while the Telegraph reached 6 percent and The
Times 2 percent.
</TEXT>
