<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0456 01-28 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0456,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Says He's Happy With Government Position</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Walesa news conference today,
PICKS UP 7th pvs `Participants also...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A buoyant Lech Walesa said today he was
satisfied with the government's offer to legalize Solidarity and
that the country's political outlook had changed.
   Speaking at a news conference after talks with the government
Friday, Walesa said the ruling Communist Party has provided
``political guarantees or political openness _ and I think it's
sufficient as a guarantee.''
   He also said upcoming talks between the government and
opposition, including Solidarity, should progress as quickly as
possible because Poland's problems are urgent.
   ``Lech Walesa is really scared,'' he said. ``The situation in the
country is very difficult.
   ``But there are terribly difficult and complicated problems and
they can't be solved that quickly,'' he added.
   The government and Solidarity leaders announced Friday in a joint
communique that talks on re-legalization of the banned Solidarity
trade movement and on political and economic reform would begin Feb.
6, according to the state news agency PAP.
   The statement also said Friday's session ``discussed the problems
of trade union pluralism, including Solidarity.''
   ``I am satisfied and very tired,'' Walesa had told reporters
after negotiating Friday for more than 11 hours to set the date for
the broader talks. ``I made hours of overtime.''
   The joint statement said a preliminary decision had been made to
set up three working teams for economic and social policy, political
reforms and union pluralism.
   Participants also agreed to set up groups on agriculture, mining,
legal and court reform, self-government, mass media and youth, the
communique said.
   Friday's talks were held in a secluded government house in the
woods in Magdalenka, a Warsaw suburb.
   The government first proposed the talks on Poland's future during
a wave of strikes in August, the country's worst labor unrest since
the government imposed martial law in December 1981 and crushed
Solidarity, the Soviet bloc's only independent trade union movement.
   The talks appear to be part of a government effort to bring the
opposition into the battle to reverse the economic decline that has
left Poland with chronic shortages, a daunting foreign debt and a
dispirited generation of young people.
   Walesa was accompanied to the negotiations by a group of seven
union activists and advisers, and three representatives of the
church.
   Others with Walesa included Gdansk Bishop Tadeusz Goclowski;
Zbigniew Bujak, the former underground Solidarity leader; and
Mieczyslaw Gil, chairman of Solidarity at the Nowa Huta steel mill
in Krakow.
   Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, Politburo member
Stanislaw Ciosek, and Janusz Reykowski, head of state-radio and
television, were among the representatives of the authorities, PAP
said.
   Walesa has said he would not hold talks on Poland's future until
the authorities made a political decision to make the union legal.
   In a dramatic reversal of policy last week, the Communist Party
Central Committee approved an offer to allow more than one legal
trade union to exist and opposition participation in the government.
   Solidarity, founded in 1980, was crushed in a December 1981
military crackdown and banned the next year.
</TEXT>
