<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 0956EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-NATO     01-28 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NATO,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Official Backs Nuclear Missile Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Rupert Scholz told
NATO defense specialists he supports plans to modernize short-range
nuclear missiles in Europe.
   However, critics at the NATO session immediately fired back that
his speech was too vague in outlining West Germany's position on a
Pentagon call for extending the range of such missiles.
   U.S. Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., told Scholz that it appeared
``you kind of want to have it both ways.''
   In his speech to NATO defense experts meeting in Munich, Scholz
laid out a middle ground between the Pentagon proposals and West
German public opinion, which is strongly against such changes.
   Scholz said only that North Atlantic Treaty Organization missiles
``must be kept modern.'' He gave no details.
   The first day of the annual weekend strategy conference produced
heated debate over various issues facing the alliance's 16 members.
   When Scholz mentioned West Germany's resistance to picking up
more of NATO's expenses, U.S. participants charged that Europeans
have not been pulling their financial weight.
   U.S. Defense Secretary-designate John Tower got a round of
applause when he arrived at the conference but sat quietly through
the sharp exchanges.
   Another major issue was how the West should respond to Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's disarmament overtures.
   A 1983 NATO decision to refit existing short-range missiles to
extend their range beyond the current limit of 300 miles is
increasingly unpopular among Europeans, especially West Germans.
Many of them see the plan as an obstacle to further arms control
reductions.
   Scholz echoed Pentagon skepticism about the Kremlin's willingness
to relinquish its military might but skirted direct mention of West
Germany's attitude toward missile modifications.
   In the dispute over NATO expenses, Rudman said that as much as 60
percent of the U.S. military budget goes for NATO-related defense.
He said European members must accept additional alliance costs.
   Edward Luttwak of Georgetown University told the gathering that
``in the last 20 years, other people have been living inside the
house of strategic security without paying the rent.''
   Scholz also drew fire from West German opposition Social Democrat
Karsten Voigt, who said the defense minister failed to take a clear
stand on the issue of missile modifications.
   ``You were really perfect when it comes to being vague,'' said
Voigt, who opposes the proposed modifications.
</TEXT>
