<FIRST>r i PM-Brazil-RareBook 1stLd-Writethru a0483 01-28 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil-Rare Book, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0483,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rare 16th Century Book Vanishes From University</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to ADD time element, PICKS UP 4th pvs
```It's worth...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare first edition of the 16th
century book ``Rimas,'' considered the Portuguese equivalent to the
works of Shakespeare, has vanished from Rio's Federal University,
officials said.
   The missing 1595 ``Rimas,'' or ``Rhymes,'' by Luis de Camoes, is
one of only six copies of the book known to exist, said Edwaldo
Machado Cafezeiro, head of the university's literature school.
   Its value is incalculable, Cafezeiro said in announcing Thursday
that the book was missing.
   ``It's worth a fortune to a collector _ $10 million is very
possible,'' he said. ``And there is a market for rare works.''
   The yellowed book disappeared after rains and floods last year
damaged the university library, Cafezeiro said. Rare books in the
collection were moved to dry rooms, but an inventory later showed
150 to 200 works were missing.
   Also among the missing was a valuable second edition of ``Rimas''
published in 1598, Cafezeiro said. However, the gem of the
collection, a copy of Camoes' other masterpiece, ``Os Lusiadas,''
was saved.
   After months of searching, the university called the federal
police. The investigation was kept secret at the request of police
until now.
   ``We need help to recover this work. It's a genuine treasure of
Brazil,'' Cafezeiro said.
   The theft of antiques is common in Brazil, especially the robbery
of carvings and precious metal ornaments from the many colonial-era
churches.
</TEXT>
