<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--WWIITunnels     01-28 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--WWII Tunnels,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>World War II Tunnels Built By British Found In Malaysia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military plans to ask Britain
to provide maps of recently discovered air defense tunnels built in
Malaysian jungles during World War II, the Bernama news agency
reported Saturday.
   The maps will help search teams trace the entrance to the
tunnels, which were discovered near Ipoh airport, the state agency
said, quoting army officials. Ipoh is 120 miles northwest of the
capital, Kuala Lumpur.
   Maj. Ismail Abdul Jalil said London will be asked to provide
information on other structures found at the site, including an air
raid shelter, a concrete fort and watchtower, a barracks and a
bunker, Bernama said.
   They were found by workers clearing the jungle in a $12 million
project to expand the airport. The government plans to preserve the
area for tourists in this former British colony off the southeast
tip of Asia.
