<HEAD>Patient Dies In Hospital Fire; Police Suspect Arson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEEDS, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire at a Leeds hospital in northern
England early Saturday killed one patient. Police said they suspect
arson.
   Staff at the city's 1,500-bed St. James' Hospital evacuated 40
choking patients from four wards as acrid smoke swirled through a
hospital block.
   The 71-year-old victim is believed to have died from inhaling
smoke. Five of the 40 firemen needed medical treatment after
inhaling the smoke.
   Ian Donnachie, the hospital's general manager, said two fires
broke out shortly after midnight, one at each end of the block.
   West Yorkshire police said an arsonist probably started the fires.
   Donnachie said a nurse raised the alarm after spotting smoke
pouring into the block. He said the fumes funneled up a laundry
chute.
   St. James' is one of Europe's largest teaching hospitals. It is
part of Britain's state-funded National Health Service.
