<FIRST>u a PM-ChallengerAnniversary 1stLd-Writethru a0411 01-28 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Challenger Anniversary, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0411,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Silent Tribute Held For Challenger Astronauts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with ceremony held; Picks up 4th
graf, `Most workers ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Space workers paid silent tribute
today to the seven astronauts who died in the Challenger explosion
three years ago.
   Flags at the Kennedy Space Center were lowered to half-staff at
11:38 a.m., the moment the space shuttle Challenger lifted off
launch pad 39B on Jan. 28, 1986. For 73 seconds, the length of the
fatal flight, all activity stopped as workers remembered the worst
disaster in the history of space exploration.
   Only about 1,000 of the center's 17,000 employees were at work
because of the weekend. Hundreds of visitors touring the space
center also joined in the tribute.
   Most workers were on duty Friday, and they paused briefly to
honor the Challenger crew a day before the anniversary.
   ``We won't forget the sacrifice made by these seven fallen
heroes,'' Forrest S. McCartney, director of the Kennedy Space
Center, told the workers in a brief televised message.
   ``We promised them we'd push on in the years to come, to fly the
space shuttle again, to continue the exploration of space as they
wanted us to,'' he said. ``We're fulfilling that promise.''
   Meanwhile, peace activists were gathering at a public park for a
demonstration this afternoon at the space center. Bruce Gagnon of
Orlando, the organizer, said the group will rally outside a center
gate to protest the launch of Defense Department payloads aboard the
shuttle.
   Discovery, which made the first post-Challenger flight last
September, is being readied to return to orbit in late February, the
first of seven flights planned in 1989. The target date is Feb. 23,
but preparations are behind schedule and officials expect a
postponement of at least two or three days.
   The launch could be pushed into March or later if engineers don't
learn soon why cracks developed in a main engine turbopump during
Atlantis' liftoff in December. Until the problem is resolved, the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration will not clear
Discovery for launch. Shuttle managers were to assess the problem
over the weekend.
</TEXT>
