<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     01-28 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brite &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The activities coordinator at Escambia
County Nursing Home is a clown.
   So is a professor of social work at the University of West
Florida.
   Ditto for one of the university's statistical research
assistants, a retired Navy officer and a couple of preschool
teachers in this Florida Panhandle city.
   They are among thousands of Americans who clown around in their
spare time.
   ``There's a little bit of clown in all of us. You just have to
bring it out,'' said Martha Morgan, a Montessori teacher who becomes
``Mo'' when she puts on her clown makeup.
   About 20 years ago, clowns were seldom seen outside circuses, and
even circus clowns were a dying breed.
   Then the Ringling Brothers and Barnum &amp; Bailey Circus established
its Clown College in Sarasota. Growth in clowning of all sorts has
been explosive.
   ``Our membership now is over 4,000,'' said Hunter ``Mr. Boots''
Stevens of West Bend, Wis., a director and past president of Clowns
of America. He said membership growns 600 or more a year.
   Janet ``Jelly Bean'' Tucker of Hammond, Ind., said some are
trying to lighten up their lives because they have straight-laced
occupations. She cited a funeral director as one example.
   ``I can't count the number of people who I have taught to clown
who quit seeing their psychiatrists,'' she said. ``When you clown,
it's the real you that comes out.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the co-owner of Colorado Industrial Saw and
Carbide opened an envelope from the local utility, she spotted a
check for nearly $60,000.
   But it turned out to be fool's gold, and Public Service Co. of
Colorado told Karen Hudson ``to please not cash it, and to not think
about vacation plans.''
   Ms. Hudson and her husband, Dana, own the saw-sharpening shop,
and sometimes do work on PSC equipment. But they knew Friday when
they saw the check for $59,287.54 that this wasn't just another
payment.
   ``I knew that those Public Service bills are awful high. I
thought maybe they were sending me a refund,'' Ms. Hudson said,
tongue firmly in cheek.
   Ms. Hudson said it turned out her company's vendor number is the
same as another PSC customer's purchase order number.
   ``It was one of those one-in-a-million things that happens,''
said utility spokeswoman Peggy Morton. ``It was a small department
that handles about 16,000 payments a month. They were rushed at the
end of the month, so I guess they got a couple of numbers
transposed.''
</TEXT>
