<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 1155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Panama     01-28 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama's Opposition Hopes For Help From Late President's Coattails</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ghost of a man deposed three times
by the military is riding the campaign trail as Panama's opposition
tries again to defeat Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and bring civilian
rule to this country.
   ``It is going to be the people against the military,'' said
Guillermo Endara, 52, who is running for president under the banner
of a coalition formed in memory of the late Arnulfo Arias Madrid.
   The elections are scheduled for May 7.
   The government candidate, to be selected shortly, will be backed
by the resources of Noriega, head of Panama's military.
   In traditional Panamanian fashion, the Arias legacy is claimed by
several political factions, anti- and pro-government.
   Arias died in August at age 86, and his burial brought forth the
largest public demonstration ever of loyalty to a Panamanian
politician.
   Some of the opposition's leaders have been expelled from the
country, and the Endara coalition is counting on Arias' popularity
and the appeal of his widow, Mireya, for a strong showing in the
elections.
   Politicians and others interviewed last week by The Associated
Press said a ticket led by Endara, a former Arias collaborator, is
not the best strategy for victory. But they hope to turn the
elections into a referendum on Noriega.
   On the ticket as candidates for Panama's two vice presidential
posts are Ricardo Arias Calderon of the small but well-organized
Christian Democrat Party and Guillermo Ford of the Liberal
Republican Movement.
   ``We do not have any illusion about the elections, but they will
be another chance for the people to show their rejection of the
military regime,'' said Carlos Valencia, president of the
Industrialists Association and a member of the Civic Crusade, an
organization of civic and independent business groups.
   The military closed the offices of the Industrialists'
Association seven months ago. News media favorable to the opposition
were closed early last year.
   Opposition leaders say privately they do not expect Noriega to
surrender power if his supporters lose the elections.
   But they hope ``a political event will happen that will bring us
closer to democracy,'' said one politician, who requested anonymity.
``Maybe they will postpone the elections or Noriega will be
overthrown by other military.''
   Noriega has survived more than a year of U.S. attempts to
overthrow him, including an indictment on federal drug-related
charges in Florida and sanctions that have battered Panama's economy.
   He broke a general strike, crushed public demonstrations and
presented himself in this country and abroad as a defender of
Panamanian sovereignty.
   Noriega says the United States wants him out to make it easier
for it to renege on the Panama Canal treaties, which call for U.S.
forces to leave in the year 2000.
   He has been in command since 1983 and could run for president as
a civilian. But it is believed Noriega will back a civilian from the
government's Revolutionary Democratic Party.
   Since taking over, Noriega has deposed three presidents; he
installed the current president, Manuel Solis Palma, in February
last year.
   Noriega was in charge in 1984 when, in the first presidential
election in 16 years, Arias lost a close election tainted by charges
of fraud.
   Arias was overthrown by the military in 1941 after one year in
power, in 1948 after almost two years and in 1968 after 11 days.
   Endara and his group were expelled from Arias's Authentic
Panamanian Party by another faction that now is expected to field
its own opposition candidate.
   ``They (the opposition) will be divided again,'' said Tomas
Altamirano Duque, editor of the newspaper La Estrella and a
government party congressman.
   The government is confident it will win the elections, he said.
</TEXT>
