<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--China-Accidents     01-28 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--China-Accidents,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says 4,000 Died in 1988 Mine Accidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 4,000 miners died in 1988, the worst
year for mine disasters in communist China's history, an official
newspaper said Saturday.
   Quoting from the China Labor and Personnel Journal, China Daily
said fatalities doubled from 1987, when about 2,200 people died in
mine accidents.
   It did not give specific numbers and the Labor Ministry does not
disclose casualties in mine accidents.
   The newspaper said that in November alone at least 477 miners
died in accidents, and 65 percent of the accidents were caused by
gas explosions.
   China is the world's largest producer of coal, but only half the
nation's coal mines are mechanized.
   Most accidents occur in the small operations run privately or by
rural collectives that ignore safety regulations or cannot afford to
implement them.
</TEXT>
