<HEAD>Deliberations Continue in Steinberg Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE with jury resuming deliberations.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury in the Joel Steinberg murder trial
reviewed testimony about the fatal beating of his 6-year-old
daughter and gave indications that deliberations could stretch into
a second week.
   On Friday, the jury asked to review testimony that could help
them judge whether Hedda Nussbaum, Steinberg's former live-in
companion, was physically capable of causing the injuries that
killed Lisa Steinberg.
   It was the sixth note from the jury since it began deliberations
around midday Monday. The jury retired at 8 p.m. Friday and resumed
deliberations at 11:40 a.m. today.
   Indications were that the jury was far from a verdict. On
Thursday, the sequestered jurors asked the judge to allow relatives
to bring them changes of clothing for several days. On Friday,
several jurors inquired about weekend religious services. Others
told employers that they might not be at work on Monday.
   Steinberg, 47, a disbarred lawyer, was charged with murder for
allegedly fatally beating Lisa, whom he illegally adopted from an
unwed mother. Lisa was removed comatose from Steinberg's Greenwich
Village apartment Nov. 2, 1987, and died of a brain injury three
days later.
   The defense claims the girl was beaten by Ms. Nussbaum, 46.
   Prosecutors responded that Ms. Nussbaum, who testified against
Steinberg and was not charged, was herself too badly battered and
emotionally disabled to have beaten the child.
   The case has focused national attention on the duty and ability
of neighbors, teachers and social workers to recognize and report
evidence of child abuse.
