<FIRST>r a PM-LaRouche 1stLd-Writethru a0413 01-28 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LaRouche, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0413,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBs 2nd graf with two new grafs to CORRECT unrepaid loans to
$294,000; pick up 3rd graf pvs: He could ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Followers of political cult leader Lyndon
H. LaRouche Jr. say they will hold a round-the-clock vigil near the
White House until he is released from federal prison. Government
lawyers say that won't happen for at least five years.
   LaRouche, 66, a three-time presidential fringe candidate, was
sentenced Friday to 15 years for scheming to defraud the Internal
Revenue Service and deliberately failing to repay loans from his
political supporters.
   Evidence showed LaRouche's fund-raising activities produced more
than $30 million and that he failed to repay $294,000 in such loans.
   He could have received a maximum of 65 years in prison and fines
totaling $3.25 million for his conviction on 13 counts of tax and
mail fraud and conspiracy.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Markham says LaRouche will serve a
minimum of five years in a yet-undecided prison before he is
eligible for parole.
   LaRouche and six associates were transferred in handcuffs from
U.S. District Court to the city jail in this Washington suburb
before being assigned permanently to a federal prison.
   The six associates received lesser penalties, ranging from three
to five years' imprisonment and fines of $6,000 to $11,000, for
their roles in the fund-raising scheme.
   LaRouche was convicted by a federal trial jury Dec. 16 on all 13
counts of an indictment charging him with tax and mail fraud
conspiracy. It was his first criminal conviction in a long and
controversial political career.
   While Chief U.S. District Judge Albert V. Bryan Jr. was imposing
sentences Friday, government prosecutors dropped all charges in a
related case in Boston against LaRouche, six aides and five
political organizations.
   The U.S. Attorney's office in Boston said that case, involving
allegations that LaRouche's 1984 presidential campaign raised more
than $2 million through credit card and loan fraud, was being
abandoned because of the successful prosecution in Alexandria.
   LaRouche attorney Odin Anderson said all seven defendants are
appealing. Bryan denied their request Friday to be released on bail
pending the outcome of their appeals.
   Before his sentencing, LaRouche told the judge that ``in effect I
was consigned to hell'' because he had rejected a deal offered by
high-level figures in ``the Anglo-American liberal establishment''
with an implicit promise of lenient treatment in court.
   LaRouche did not say what the alleged deal involved, but said it
underscored his belief that government prosecutors were seeking to
``eliminate me from the political scene.''
   Bryan snapped that claims of political motivation behind the case
were ``arrant nonsense.'' But LaRouche said it was ``time for this
evil and reckless prosecution to be brought to a halt before further
damage is done'' to U.S. national security interests.
   The judge said he was bothered that none of the defendants had
conceded wrongdoing or expressed remorse over the millions of
dollars in defaulted loans they took from LaRouche supporters, many
of them elderly retirees whose life savings were lost.
   One of the seven defendants, LaRouche legal coordinator Edward
Spannaus, said that ``remorse should be felt by those who perverted
our judicial system for political purposes and trampled on the
Constitution.''
   LaRouche spokeswoman Dana Scanlon said a small group of
demonstrators had begun a nonstop vigil in Lafayette Park, across
Pennsylvania Avenue from the White House, with a large, illuminated
sign reading ``Pardon LaRouche.'' She said the sign will be within
President Bush's view from the White House.
   In Mexico City on Friday, about a dozen LaRouche supporters held
a protest march in front of the Monument of Independence, also known
as the angel. They carried signs that read ``LaRouche is Innocent.''
</TEXT>
