<DOCNO> AP890128-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 1259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Sullivan-Abortion Bjt   01-28 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sullivan-Abortion, Bjt,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Impact on Health Programs Seen in Row Over Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans to place staunch pro-lifers in top posts
at the Health and Human Services Department could have deep impact
on family planning, fetal research and other key programs, say
activists on the abortion issue.
   ``Just about any abortion issue that has to do with the medical
delivery system will touch HHS in some fashion,'' Douglas Johnson of
the National Right to Life Committee said last week following an
agreement to ensure strong pro-life representation in the
department's top echelons.
   The agreement from the administration came in response to concern
among pro-life lawmakers that President Bush's nominee for HHS
secretary, Dr. Louis Sullivan, could be lacking in anti-abortion
fervor.
   ``There's no office aside from the presidency that's more
influential in advancing the right-to-life agenda,'' said Sen.
Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., an fervent advocate of outlawing abortion.
   Humphrey, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and Rep. Vin Weber, R-Minn.,
struck a deal last week with the White House: They would agree to
Sullivan's nomination and Bush would fill other top slots at the
agency with pro-lifers.
   White House chief of staff John Sununu later announced that
Sullivan had recommended Constance J. Horner, head of the Office of
Personnel Management, as HHS undersecretary.
   James O. Mason, director of the Centers for Disease Control, was
Sullivan's choice fpr assistant secretary for health, a position
that oversees the National Institutes of Health, among other
agencies.
   Both are well known as foes of abortion, Sununu said.
   Administration sources also said Kay James, a former spokeswoman
for the National Right to Life Committee, has been recommended for
assistant secretary for public affairs.
   All three would be in positions to make and influence policy.
While Congress defines the broad outlines, its dictates on complex
health issues usually leave the department with ample room to
maneuver in enforcing the law and making rules and regulations.
   The system puts considerable power in the hands of department
officials.
   Concern among activists over the key positions is sharper than
usual because the Surpreme Court recently agreed to hear a case that
could narrow the legalization of abortion it decreed in the landmark
1973 Roe vs. Wade decision.
   Sullivan, himself, was stung last week when one lawmaker quoted
the prospective secretary as saying he opposed overturning the Roe
vs. Wade ruling. A Capitol Hill flareup ensued, but Sullivan quickly
quelled the turmoil by meeting with with anti-abortion lawmakers and
assured them he supported Bush's pro-life position.
   Sullivan's nomination already had raised concerns of
anti-abortion activists earlier when he was quoted in a newspaper
article as saying he opposed abortion and he favored a woman's right
to choose. Later, he said he supported Bush's view that abortion
should be allowed only in cases of rape, incest and danger to the
life of the mother.
   Pro-choice forces say that even in the Reagan administration,
with ties to the anti-abortion movement, there have usually been at
least some restraints.
   Jo Ann Gasper, an abortion foe, was fired as deputy assistant
secretary for population affairs in 1987 when she tried to block
federal funds for Planned Parenthood family planning programs on
grounds the organization also advocates abortion.
   ``That shows the possibilities and the limitations,'' said Nancy
Broff, legislative and political director of the National Abortion
Rights Action League. ``It shows that people at that level have a
fair amount (of power) to do good or do harm, because the secretary
can't make every decision. But it also shows there can be some
limits on what they can get away with.''
   Those family planning grants are still an important issue at HHS.
After the Gasper firing, the department rewrote the guidelines for
the $138 million in grants to deny funding to programs that include
abortion counseling and referral in their services.
   Three lawsuits have been filed challenging the regulations. Two
federal courts have ruled against the regulations, one has ruled in
favor and appeals have been filed in all three cases.
   Abortions are covered by the Medicaid program, the federal-state
insurance program for the poor that is administered by HHS, only if
the life of the mother is in danger _ a relatively rare occurence.
In fiscal year 1988, federal Medicaid funds covered 84 abortions, at
a cost of $61,235, HHS said.
   An estimated 1.5 million legal abortions are performed each year.
   Abortion foes say that though Congress has restricted Medicaid
funding of abortions for the past 10 years, HHS administrators have
some discretion in deciding whether to allow coverage in their
case-by-case reviews.
</TEXT>
