<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Libya     01-28 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Libya,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Genscher Proposes Meeting With Baker On Libyan Chemical Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NATO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign minister has written to
U.S. Secretary of State James Baker proposing the two men confer on
how to prevent Libya from producing chemical weapons, the ministry
said Saturday.
   News of the letter comes amid U.S. accusations that West German
leaders looked the other way while German companies helped Libya
build a chemical plant allegedly capable of producing poison gas.
   West German leaders deny they ignored American charges that
German firms were involved in the Libyan plant and point out that
prosecutors are investigating a number of companies believed linked
to the complex.
   The letter from minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher appeared to be
part of West Germany's efforts to persuade American officials this
country is seriously concerned that German companies may have broken
export laws with shipments to Libya and other countries.
   In his letter to Baker, Genscher proposed ``joint discussions
over measures for the prevention of chemical weapons production in
Libya,'' the West German Foreign Ministry said in a telex to the
news media.
   The statement did not explain what measures those would entail.
   But the Welt am Sonntag newspaper said Saturday that Chancellor
Helmut Kohl plans ``an act of solidarity with Western industrial
nations to make sure that Libya does not receive missing
construction components and materials necessary for the production
of chemical weapons.''
   ``Kohl is making efforts in talks with the allies for such a
joint initiative,'' Welt am Sonntag said.
   Former Secretary of State George P. Shultz said before leaving
office last week that the Libyan plant had not reached the point of
production and that it might not get there if Western companies
heeded U.S. warnings.
   Libya claims the plant is intended for the production of
pharmaceuticals, and not poison gases.
   Welt am Sonntag said it got its information from ``sources in the
chancellor's office.'' The newspaper telexed copies of its report to
other news organizations in advance of Sunday's publication.
   According to the West German Foreign Ministry telex, Genscher
also has urged that the European Economic Community launch ``a joint
initiative ... with the goal of preventing the spread of chemical
weapons.''
   West Germany's export controls have come under increasing attack
in the past few weeks because of the Libyan scandal, reports of West
German help in building a suspected mustard gas plant in Iraq, and
alleged shipments of materials that can be used to make atomic bombs
to Pakistan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
