<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0517 01-28 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0517,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fighting Rages In Lebanon, Despite Efforts By Syria, Iran</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with other bombing in Beirut, new
casualty toll and U.S. comment on embassy incident. Pickup 6th pvs, ``He
described...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite attempts by Syria and Iran to stop
the violence in Lebanon, two bombs exploded Saturday and Shiite
Moslem militias battled once again. Two people were reported killed
and 20 injured.
   Police said one person was killed and 11 people injured,
including a Syrian soldier, when a car exploded in the Bekaa town of
Barr Elias.
   In a separate attack, a bomb exploded at a building in Moslem
west Beirut near a Syrian army checkpoint, wounding six people,
police said.
   A 90-minute firefight between the pro-Syrian Amal militia and the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, in the slums of south
Beirut killed one person and wounded three, according to police.
   In an unprecedented incident at the American Embassy, local staff
locked Ambassador John McCarthy in his office for three hours on
Friday to press for higher salaries, an embassy source said Saturday.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Nancy Beck said
Lebanese guards had mounted a ``work action'' but refused to give
details. ``The issues are economic and are being dealt with,'' she
said.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing rules,
said a Syrian army ambulance took the wounded Syrian soldier from
the site of the car bomb explosion to a Syrian field clinic in the
Bekaa valley.
   He described the wounded Lebanese as ``civilians.''
   Ambulances, their sirens wailing, evacuated the wounded Lebanese
to a hospital in the Bekaa valley town of Zahleh where they were
treated for ``minor wounds and discharged,'' the spokesman said.
   He said the car-bombing, the second in Lebanon this year, also
set ablaze eight parked cars and damaged 12 stores.
   The first car-bombing occurred in the south Beirut slum of Bir
Abed on Jan. 13, killing seven people and wounded 15. By police
count, 116 people were killed and 448 wounded in 20 car bombings in
Lebanon in 1988.
   The police spokesman said Amal and Hezbollah militiamen traded
machine gun fire and rocket-propelled grenades until 7:30 a.m., when
the Syrian command dispatched patrols to the contested region to
impose a cease-fire.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 40,000 troops
in the Bekaa and the northern province as well as in west and south
Beirut.
   The latest casualties raised the overall toll to 173 killed and
340 wounded since a new round of Amal-Hezbollah fighting broke out
in south Beirut Dec. 31 and spread to south Lebanon's apple province.
   Amal and Hezbollah are vying for dominance of the 1 million
Shiites, the largest sect in Lebanon.
   Hezbollah, made up of Shiite zealots, seeks to found an Islamic
republic in Lebanon patterned after Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's
regime in Iran. The more secular Amal, Arabic for hope, favors a
multisect government that would give Moslems and Christians an equal
share of power.
   By police count, 500 people were killed and 1,500 wounded in
three previous major confrontations between Amal and Hezbollah since
April.
   The fighting continues despite a concerted effort by Syria and
Iran to set and enforce cease-fires in Lebanon.
   The American embassy source, who insisted on not being identified
further, said the ambassador was freed Friday night and promised to
take up the local employees' demands with Washington.
   He said the employees demanded ``increases in salaries and were
protesting the lack of benefits for their families.''
   During the protest, staff members _ including guards armed with
rifles _ blocked entrances to the embassy compound in the Christian
suburb of Aukur, the source said.
   It was not known how many of the 500-strong local staff joined
the protest. McCarthy, 49, took up his post Sept. 24 after the
previous ambassador, John Kelly, left because of illness.
   The situation at the embassy was normal Saturday, the source
added.
</TEXT>
