<FIRST>r a AM-People     01-28 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0747</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City's biggest blowout of the new year
is scheduled this week as Princess Diana flies in for a three-day
stay that includes a visit with young AIDS victims as well as social
hobnobbing.
   It will be the first look at New York for the wife of England's
next king. Diana's previous visit to the United States, in 1985,
took her to the White House with her husband, Prince Charles.
   The princess, this time traveling without her prince, is
scheduled to arrive Wednesday. The following evening she will lure
battalions of beautiful people to the Brooklyn Academy of Music for
the American debut of the Welsh National Opera.
   Following the $1,000-a-seat performance of ``Falstaff,'' a line
of limousines will take the 850 ticket buyers back to lower
Manhattan for dinner with Diana at the Winter Garden atrium of the
World Financial Center.
   Among the lions at the festivities will be screen actor Michael
Douglas, Happy Rockefeller, widow of Nelson, a former vice
president, publisher Malcolm Forbes, developer Donald Trump and
social arbiter Brooke Astor.
   Less frothy fare is on the menu too _ a trip Thursday morning to
the Henry Street Settlement on the lower East Side for a look at day
care and a self-help group session; Friday morning a ride to Harlem
Hospital for a visit with children suffering from AIDS.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comic actor Pinky Lee is recuperating from a
heart attack with a newly installed pacemaker, the veteran
entertainer's daughter said.
   ``Dad is coming along, but he has suffered a massive heart attack
with extensive damage to his heart,'' said Patti Lee, who spoke from
St. Francis Medical Center where her father is being treated.
   Lee, described by his daughter Friday as about 72 years old, was
stricken Wednesday night during a performance of the
vaudeville-style Broadway musical ``Sugar Babies.''
   ``He was waiting in the wings for his final part ... when he said
`I don't feel good' and turned white,'' Ms. Lee said. ``He was
drenched in sweat and began to feel nausea and someone called a
medic. That was it.''
   Lee began his entertainment career at age 3, when he started
touring with professional child reviews. He went on to nightclubs,
Broadway, radio and television.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Rogers, ``the king of the cowboys,''
and country music star Randy Travis have become a duet.
   The two said Friday night that they recorded Rogers' theme song,
``Happy Trails to You.''
   Travis said the song was the first one he has recorded for an
album of duets. He did not say who his other singing partners will
be or when the record will be released.
   Travis and Rogers discussed the project Friday on The Nashville
Network's ``Nashville Now'' program.
   Rogers is a member of the Country Music Hall of Fame for his
western singing. Travis has recorded a string of No. 1 hits,
including the current ``Deeper Than the Holler'' and ``Forever and
Ever, Amen.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Stovall, a junior forward on the Boston
College basketball team, was in stable condition Saturday after
suffering a stroke in his dormitory bathroom, a doctor reported.
   Stovall, 22, of Scarborough, Maine, suffered a blood clot on the
left side of his brain and suffered some weakness in his right side
Friday morning. The stroke was not basketball-related, said Dr.
Ellen Lahti, a neurologist at St. Elizabeth's Hospital.
   Lahti said it was too soon to know how it will affect Stovall.
   ``He's in good spirits and working very hard to get better,'' she
said. ``All his friends and teammates were there to visit him and
they accompanied him to the hospital.''
   The 6-foot-6-inch Stovall averaged 3.3 points and 1.8 rebounds in
12 games for Boston College.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music singer Steve Wariner plans
a Feb. 19 benefit concert for a terminally ill Kentucky state
trooper in Pineville, Ky.
   Wariner said the concert at the Bell County High School Gym will
go toward the medical expenses of Randy Gardner, who has cancer.
   Wariner said he was contacted about the situation by three of
Gardner's friends, who also are state troopers.
   The singer's No. 1 hits include ``Small Town Girl,'' ``Lynda''
and ``The Weekend.''
