<FIRST>r a AM-AmishJailed     01-28 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amish Jailed,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amish Man Jailed For Refusing Son's Cancer Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETHTOWN, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of a small Amish community who
refuses to turn his 6-year-old son over to a hospital for cancer
treatment has been jailed on a contempt of court charge.
   Danny Mast argued that chemotherapy was not helping his son,
Amos, who has abdominal cancer, and that the boy has done much
better on ``natural medicine,'' such as herbs and vitamins, that he
learned at a clinic in Mexico.
   Mast, who lives 15 miles from Elizabethtown in Sonora in Hardin
County, was jailed Friday after a closed hearing before District
Judge Janet Coleman.
   ``This is not only his decision, it's the decision of the whole
group,'' said James Gregory, a court-appointed attorney for Mast.
``Religion permeates everything they do. They believe they are
better off to trust God then to get back in the chemotherapy, which
they feel would affect the remaining quality of this child's life.''
   The Amish religion teaches separation from the world, with plain
dress and living, and little reliance on modern conveniences.
   ``We try to do without what we think we can get along without,''
said Eli Troyer, one of the community's three preachers. ``We do
things like chemotherapy if we don't find anything better, but we
think we have.''
   Troyer said the chemotherapy was like a poison and made the boy
worse. Since beginning the natural medication, Amos is looking
better, Troyer said.
   Mast declined to comment.
   Mast's only requests at the jail were to be allowed to keep his
family Bible with him and to be put in a cell by himself, both of
which were honored, said Jailer Louis Lawson. ``The man was very
calm very polite, very well-mannered.''
   The child's physician at Kosair Children's Hospital in Louisville
believes the boy is in danger without a medically proven treatment
and filed the petition in Hardin juvenile court seeking to resume
therapy in December. The hospital contacted the county attorney's
office again this month because the child had never returned.
   At a previous hearing, Mast produced an X-ray that he said shows
his son's tumor had shrunk as a result of the natural treatment.
   Gregory said the only way Mast could be released now is if the
boy is produced or the case is decided otherwise _ if the boy dies,
for example.
   But the lawyer said Mast has told him he does not know where the
boy is and will not produce his son.
   Mast is part of a conclave of 15 Amish families who moved from
Tennessee to southern Hardin County three years ago. German is
spoken in the community and homes lack electricity and running
water. The children attend a one-room Amish school.
   State officials say the family has hidden the boy and believe he
is in another Amish community. They said he would be taken into
state custody if he is found, and the chemotherapy treatments
resumed.
   However, friends and relatives who accompanied Mast to the
hearing said the boy would not be turned over.
   Mast's father-in-law, Monroe Miller, said he believes his
grandson is being helped by the natural treatment, but that if the
boy isn't going to recover he should be able to die in peace rather
than pain.
   Miller said he was not angered by the court ruling. ``Scripture
says if they strike your right cheek, you offer your left,'' he said
as he climbed into his buggy.
   Mast's wife gave birth to a son Wednesday and did not accompany
her husband to the hearing.
   Assistant County Attorney Chris Shaw declined to comment on the
case because it involves a juvenile. All records on juvenile cases
are also closed to the public.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
