<FIRST>r a AM-Mother'sDeath     01-28 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mother's Death,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Pleads Innocent To New Charges In Mother's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose mother hid a note in her
underwear saying that her son killed her before she was found dead
two years ago has pleaded innocent to a new indictment charging him.
   ``There's no doubt he's depressed,'' Earl Gray, Richard Dziubak's
attorney, said after court Friday. ``Wouldn't you be having to face
charges again when you know you haven't done anything?''
   Dziubak, 36, originally pleaded guilty to manslaughter after he
admitted pushing his mother, May Hilda Speiser, 65, during an
argument at the top of the basement stairs in their home in February
1987. But experts later differed on whether it was the fall, or a
subsequent drug overdose, that actually killed the woman.
   Dziubak said that after she fell down the stairs, she rejected
his offers of help and walked up two floors to her bedroom. She was
found dead in bed the next day, having left a note stating, ``Dick
killed me threw me down basement.''
   Following his guilty plea, Dziubak was sentenced in June 1987 to
an 81-month prison term. Ramsey County District Judge Allan Markert
released Dziubak in November 1988 and allowed him to withdraw his
plea because of the experts' conflicting views on what had actually
killed the woman.
   On Wednesday, a grand jury indicted Dziubak on charges of
second-degree murder, second-degree manslaughter and third-degree
assault.
   On Friday, Markert let Dziubak remain free without bond because
the defendant had not fled the state after being released from
prison, had no record of violence and had a job.
   Gray said he will file a motion to dismiss the indictment for
lack of probable cause, and Markert set a hearing date of March 1.
Trial was scheduled for April 10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
