<FIRST>r a AM-Bundy-Tanner     01-28 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bundy-Tanner,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Who Prayed With Bundy To Leave Prison Ministry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor who prayed with Ted Bundy says
he is quitting the prison ministry program that led him to the
serial killer because of the disapproval of his constituents.
   Hundreds of phone calls and letters from people questioning State
Attorney John Tanner's involvement with Bundy before last week's
execution have reached the prosecutor's Daytona Beach office.
   Tanner said the reaction has turned from negative to ``90 percent
positive,'' but some people are discussing a recall attempt.
   ``A small percentage of the public is uncomfortable with it,''
said Tanner, a born-again Christian who exchanged letters with Bundy
for about two years and has been state attorney for about a month.
``They feel it's somehow inappropriate.
   ``I think public perception and trust is absolutely essential. I
want to keep public confidence in the office.''
   Bundy invited Tanner to visit after he wrote as part of his
prison ministry. While Bundy was on death row, Tanner visited him
about 50 times to pray and read the Bible.
   Tanner asked Gov. Bob Martinez to delay Bundy's execution last
week to give Bundy time to confess to dozens of murders he is
believed to have committed. Martinez refused, and Bundy was
electrocuted Tuesday for killing 12-year-old Kimberly Leach of Lake
City. Before his death, he confessed to 23 murders.
   Bundy's lawyer, James Coleman has said his client confessed since
1986 to ``two or three dozen'' murders in private talks with his
attorneys and psychiatrists.
   Tanner, a former criminal defense attorney, discussed his role in
Bundy's case Friday during a meeting of Volusia County police chiefs.
   He asked them to explain his role to their officers, saying:
``Please tell your people because I need their support, I need their
trust.''
   About 100 disgruntled residents pledged to attend a Sunday
meeting at the Ormond Beach home of Peggy Barbee, who said that
while the gathering is not necessarily a recall attempt, it may come
to that.
   ``We're just going to have a meeting to let people air their
feelings,'' she said.
</TEXT>
