<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 1517EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FakePregnancies     01-28 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fake Pregnancies,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor Accused Of Lying To Women About Pregnancies May Lose License</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto RHD1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state medical board committee found
sufficient evidence to warrant revoking the license of a fertility
specialist accused of telling women they were pregnant when he knew
they were not.
   A three-physician panel of the board decided at the end of a
five-hour informal hearing Friday that Dr. Cecil B. Jacobson of
Vienna violated the Virginia Medical Practices Act.
   The panel will tell the full board that it believes revocation of
Jacobson's license may be justified. The final decision would be
made after the full 16-member board holds a formal hearing.
   Jacobson, 52, credited with performing the first amniocentesis in
the United States, also was found to have defrauded six women who
paid him up to $5,000 each for fertility treatments, the panel said.
He recently closed his Tysons Corner clinic.
   Several former patients who went to Jacobson for fertility
problems and testified Friday had tears in their eyes and smiles on
their faces at the panel's finding.
   ``I couldn't figure out what I was doing to kill these babies,''
said Sharon Hayward, who owns a printing business in Camp Springs.
``I felt so guilty.'' Ms. Hayward said Jacobson told her three times
that she was pregnant when she was not.
   Jacobson's attorney, Tara McCarthy, said the accusations from the
witnesses and the nine lawsuits pending against Jacobson were the
complaints of disappointed women who had difficulty conceiving.
   ``The other side of the coin is that he has treated a lot of
patients ... who did get pregnant,'' Ms. McCarthy said. Jacobson had
no comment.
   The findings of the informal Virginia state hearing Friday will
be sent to Jacobson in writing. He then may surrender his license to
avoid further proceedings from the state board.
   The Board of Medicine charged Jacobson with injecting several
patients with a fertility drug on several occasions and conducting
numerous ultrasound examinations, telling them they were pregnant
when they were not. The drug causes symptoms that mimic pregnancy,
such as weight gain and postive urine tests.
   Jacobson also faces action from a federal agency. Earlier this
month, the Federal Trade Commission filed consumer fraud charges
against him, alleging that he told potential patients his
hormone-injection treatments had resulted in successful pregnancies
for 80 percent of his patients, when in fact no more than 40 percent
became pregnant.
   In all, said FTC Chairman Daniel Oliver, Jacobson treated
``several hundred women'' who lost a total of from $400,000 to $2
million or more. The FTC will be seeking a return of some of all of
those fees, Oliver said.
   Much of Friday's testimony concerned Jacobson's interpretation of
ultrasound tests on his patients, which seek to examine a pregnant
woman's growing fetus by the use of ultrasonic waves.
   Jacobson maintained that he detected an embryonic sac in the
ultrasound pictures, indicating pregnancy. However, he later
informed the patients that the pregnancy had ended and their bodies
had reabsorbed the fetus.
   Jacobson said he is not currently practicing and that he is
reviewing 25 years of work to prepare defense for multiple lawsuits.
   Some of the patients' complaints were the subject of a ``60
Minutes'' television segment last month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
