<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh     01-28 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scores of Bangladesh Polls Close in Violence That Kills Six</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting between rival political
candidates and their supporters forced officials to halt voting at
scores of polling stations Saturday after six people were killed and
about 200 injured, authorities said.
   Violence flared despite the deployment of 15,000 police and
village guards to protect polling stations where municipal elections
were being held.
   The Interior Ministry said it ordered the mobilization after one
person was killed and 200 injured Thursday in attacks with homemade
bombs and clubs.
   Despite the violence, the campaign was relatively peaceful
compared with past campaigns in Bangladesh.
   Representatives of the two major opposition parties boycotted
last year's parliamentary elections but are contesting these
elections. They are Sheik Hasina's Awami League and the Bangladesh
National Party of Khaleda Zia.
   Election Commission sources said 388 candidates were running for
chairmanships of the 80 councils and 3,000 others were contesting
798 council seats. The councils serve three years.
   Election officials could not give the voter turnout, but more
than 2 million people were eligible to vote Saturday.
   A police official in Dhaka, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said at least five people were killed and about 200 were injured in
clashes Saturday involving police and rival candidates.
   Another police officer in southern Mongla town said fighting
among rival supporters left another person dead there.
   Polling was suspended in scores of centers because of violence
and voting irregularities, an election officer said on condition of
anonymity. He said he did not know the precise number of polling
stations where voting was halted.
</TEXT>
