<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 1536EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-KingMuseum     01-28 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-King Museum,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Praise and Protests At Groundbreaking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Ralph Abernathy joined local
government officials and well-wishers for the groundbreaking of a
national civil rights museum on the site where Martin Luther King
Jr. was assassinated.
   Construction is to begin this week on the $8.8 million
transformation of the rundown Lorraine Motel. It is scheduled to
reopen July 4, 1991, as a museum with exhibits on major civil rights
conflicts and a tour of Room 306, where King spent his last night.
   ``I need not pause to tell you how delighted I am to return to
these sacred grounds,'' Abernathy told a crowd of about 150 on
Friday. ``I'm just glad to be here on this occasion because you are
speaking so clearly and so profoundly to the South and the whole
nation: `Get your act together.'''
   While staying at the Lorraine, King was shot to death April 4,
1968, on a motel balcony.
   Abernathy, who succeeded King as president of the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference, thanked supporters of the project
for ``building a memorial to the life of my dearest friend.''
   Memphis lawyer D'Army Bailey, who led the seven-year effort to
preserve the motel, called the decision to turn it into a museum a
victory over the ``unholy carnage'' that took place there.
   But a small group of protesters nearby said King would have
wanted to help the poor rather than make a museum. Some waived signs
such as ``Memphis, don't let his dreams die, too.''
   ``We feel our taxes could be better spent in some other way that
would be similar to Dr. King's believes,'' said a protester, Jon
McLaughlin.
   The $8.8 million cost of the museum is coming from the state,
city and Shelby County governments. Part of the motel building will
be razed and the wing where King stayed will be the centerpiece of
the museum.
   Opponents have suggested a homeless shelter or health clinic
instead. Bailey said he also favors better housing and health care,
but that the Lorraine is needed as a monument to the civil rights
struggle.
   The Lorraine began attracting visitors within months of the
shooting, after the motel's owner turned King's room into a shrine.
A city report in 1980 said 70,000 people visited the site each year
on organized tours.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
