<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 1541EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Cezanne 1stLd-Writethru a0548 01-28 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cezanne, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0548,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Exhibit At National Gallery Spotlights Early Works</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts 4th graf, Barbara Bush xxx with first lady touring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The turbulent struggles of a youthful Paul
Cezanne to develop his artistic style are spotlighted in a new
exhibition of the French master's early works, opening Sunday at the
National Gallery of Art.
   Harsh scenes of eroticism and violence appear among the
portraits, landscapes and still lifes in 57 paintings and 15
drawings from the least-known period of Cezanne's art, when he
abandoned law school and began painting in his 20s.
   Hardly any hint of Cezanne's future eminence as a major figure in
the impressionist and post-impressionist movements, or his prophetic
influence on cubism and abstract art, is evident in the exhibition,
which will run through April 30.
   Barbara Bush, wife of the president, was given a private tour of
the Cezanne showing and some other exhibits at the gallery on
Saturday.
   The show, organized by the British art historian Sir Lawrence
Gowing, debuted at the Royal Academy of Arts in London last April
and traveled to Washington _ its only U.S. appearance _ from the
Musee d'Orsay in Paris.
   Cezanne scholar John Rewald told reporters at a National Gallery
preview that the artist's early works, from the decade of the 1860s,
frequently have been dismissed as inferior to the great canvasses of
his mature years.
   But ``the early works can stand on their own feet,'' Rewald said.
``Even if he had died before his final period, we'd treasure him as
a great artist.''
   ``Whoever you pick as the father of modern art, the first father
has to be Cezanne,'' said gallery director J. Carter Brown.
   Charles Moffett, senior curator of paintings at the National
Gallery, said the exhibition is ``a portrait of the artist as a
young man'' and ``gets us into the head and mind of one of the
greatest painters of all time.''
   The paintings and drawings were selected from public and private
collections in the United States, Europe, the Soviet Union,
Australia, Brazil and Canada. To complement the show, the National
Gallery is displaying 25 later Cezanne paintings from its own
holdings and loans from the White House and three private U.S.
collections.
   The paintings in the auxiliary show are serenely contemplative,
after the emotional thrashing and self-doubts reflected in some of
Cezanne's early works next door, and they lead to another room where
Cezanne takes his place with the likes of Monet and Renoir.
   Among the later Cezanne oils is the National Gallery's ``Bend in
the Road,'' painted in the first decade of the 20th century with
pastel planes that are unmistakable precursors of the cubism of
Georges Braque and Pablo Picasso.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
