<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 1551EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Cuba-Gorbachev     01-28 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Gorbachev,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prensa Latina Reports Gorbachev To Visit Cuba In April</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev will
visit Cuba in the first week of April, the official Cuban news
agency reported Saturday.
   The visit was announced on Cuban television Saturday, the Prensa
Latina news agency said in an urgent dispatch monitored in Mexico
City.
   Gorbachev had planned a three-day visit to Cuba begining Dec. 9,
but canceled at the last minute after the devastating earthquake in
Soviet Armenia.
   Cuba sent a relief team to the stricken area and said the
invitation to Gorbachev still was open.
   There was no immediate announcement in Moscow about rescheduling
the visit, and Soviet sources have said the visit has been postponed
indefinitely.
   Although Cuban President Fidel Castro has made no secret of his
disdain for Gorbachev's reformist agenda, the Soviet leader's visit
was to feature Havana's grandest reception for a visiting dignitary.
At least 500,000 people were expected to line the route of
Gorbachev's motorcade.
   Castro's rejection of Gorbachev's economic reforms, which he said
``reek of capitalism,'' have led to speculation about a rift between
the Soviet Union and its closest ally in the Western Hemisphere.
   Cuba's economic performance is poor, and the island nation has
been a financial drain on the Soviets at a time when the Kremlin is
trying to channel resources to domestic needs. Castro also is
unsympathetic to Gorbachev's encouragement of more openness of
expression.
   Gorbachev was widely expected to try to persuade Castro to soften
his opposition to the new political thinking in the Soviet Union.
   ``We are not seeking to worsen our relations with Cuba,'' one
Latin American specialist at the Kremlin said in December. ``But
Gorbachev is a very persuasive man, and he will try to explain his
intentions.''
   The source said Cuba has become an embarrassment as well as a
financial drain on the Soviet Union. Castro is seen as an exporter
of revolution, a position that runs counter to new Soviet thinking.
   ``We are no longer supporting class wars or socialist revolution
in Latin America,'' said the Soviet specialist, who spoke to The
Associated Press in Moscow on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
