<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia     01-28 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Premier Calls For ``New Socialism'' In Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia's Premier-designate Ante
Markovic on Saturday called for radical market-oriented reforms and
a ``completly new type of socialism'' to overcome the country's deep
economic and social crisis.
   ``I consider the open-market economy to be an ultimate
achievement of mankind for which no alternative has yet been
found,'' Markovic said, advocating closer links with ``the most
developed European countries.''
   He also revealed that this communist country, with inflation
running more than 250 percent and stagnating economic growth, is
again unable to repay foreign debts.
   ``The solution to our problems does not lie in cosmetic changes
to the existing system,'' Markovic said in his speech on state
television.
   ``We should develop a completely new type of socialism in this
country ... with maximum democracy, freedom and political
pluralism,'' Markovic said in his first public address since he was
designated premier by the state presidency.
   Markovic said he accepted the premiership on the condition he
have a free hand in choosing his Cabinet.
   He said it will take at least five years to consolidate his
reforms.
   Markovic is formally to remain in office until the end of
Mikulic's original four-year mandate that expires in May 1990. The
premier designate said he would need a full mandate to implement his
economic plan.
   Markovic on March 1 is to succeed Branko Mikulic, who resigned
with his entire Cabinet on Dec. 30. It was the first federal
government to step down since the communists took power after World
War II.
   Mikulic resigned following his failure to solve the country's
numerous social and economic problems, including a dramatic
escalation of labor and ethnic unrest.
   ``All 23 million citizens of Yugoslavia should have a right to
decide about (the future of) this country ...'' Markovic said in a
clear reference to the Yugoslav Communist Party members who occupy
all leading economic and political posts.
   In May 1987, Yugoslavia was unable to repay an installment of
about $400 million of a short-term foreign loan. Without giving
details, Markovic said Yugoslavia is now faced with a similar
problem.
   ``Unless Yugoslavia is able to increase its foreign currency
earnings to between $25 billion and $28 billion a year within the
next five years ... it will not be able to set aside 25 percent of
that figure to repay its foreign debt'' and simultaneously ensure
that its economy continues to function normally, he disclosed.
   At present, the country's foreign currency earnings are about $11
billion annually. It has to devote about $7 billion annually to
service and repay its $21 billion foreign debt.
   Markovic said that joint ventures with foreign partners must have
``absolute priority.''
   He also called for an ``urgent introduction of shares and bonds,
private initiative and entrepreneurship in the Yugoslav economy''
and an end to state interference in the running of businesses.
   Other reforms would include the reshaping the banking system
along Western lines, creating a capital market and an end to state
subsidies for money-losing companies.
   Markovic said that Yugoslav workers in profitable firms should be
``stimulated to work better'' through higher salaries because ``the
impoverished worker is ready to destroy the current system.''
</TEXT>
