<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Mine     01-28 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Mine,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescuers Suspend Search at Collapsed Peru Gold Mine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers on Saturday suspended their search for
about 20 miners buried for a week in a sabotaged Peruvian gold mine,
police said.
   Three miners have been found alive and six bodies have been
recovered since a rescue began Monday at the hillside mine near
Nazca, 230 miles south of Lima.
   Official sources now say no more than 30 miners were trapped and
presumed dead, after giving conflicting figures ranging from 15 to
300.
   Nazca police said they suspended operations because rescuers were
endangered by toxic fumes, smoke from a still-burning fire, and
feeble tunnel supports that caused several new cave-ins during the
week.
   The government is evaluating whether to renew efforts after 20
rescuers were treated for inhalation of smoke and toxic gas in the
past week, said police.
   Factions battling over a rich gold vein on Jan. 21 set ablaze
timbers supporting tunnels and smoke prevented miners from escaping
the Sol de Oro mine, officials said. Flames ate through the beams
and the mine collapsed Monday, further enclosing victims.
   Hope was revived briefly Tuesday when rescuers reported tapping
from caved-in tunnels. But those sounds have not been heard since.
   Officials said it is impossible to know exactly how many people
were trapped because about 900 farmers and other area residents have
been working the mine independently for more than a year, mining
when and where they like without any control.
   Commercial mining was halted there 40 years ago because of
falling profits, officials said.
</TEXT>
