<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Kelly 1stLd-Writethru a0555 01-28 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Kelly, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0555,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Squadron Leader Robert B. Kelly Dead at 75</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last 2 grafs with 4 grafs to UPDATE with funeral arrangements,
add explanation of `expendable' description.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert B. Kelly, a retired Navy captain
whose combat experience as a PT boat commander in the Pacific during
World War II became the basis for the best-selling book and movie
``They Were Expendable,'' has died of pneumonia. He was 75.
   The former naval officer died Monday at Howard County General
Hospital.
   Kelly was executive officer of the famed Motor Torpedo Boat
Squadron 3. He won a Navy Cross, the Navy's highest decoration after
the Medal of Honor, for sinking a Japanese light cruiser off the
island of Luzon in the Philippines on the night of April 8, 1942.
   He was commander of the lead boat in the four-craft PT boat
squadron that evacuated Gen. Douglas MacArthur, his family and staff
by night from the island of Corregidor, where the U.S. forces were
trapped by the Japanese army, on March 11, 1942. He was awarded a
Silver Star for that effort.
   Later in the war, Kelly was commander of a PT boat squadron in
the Solomon Islands, where he won a second Silver Star for action in
combat against the Japanese. One of the men serving under him was
Lt. John F. Kennedy, whose boat, PT 109, sank after it was rammed by
a Japanese destroyer on the night of Aug. 2, 1943.
   Kelly was a native of New York City and a 1935 graduate of the
U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis.
   Author William L. White based ``They Were Expendable'' on the
experience of Squadron 3 in the Philippines, and actor John Wayne
played the part of Kelly in the 1945 movie.
   His wife, Barbara Lee Benedict Kelly, said her husband called the
Pacific fleet ``expendable'' because the Navy could get few supplies
to it around the Japanese forces.
   ``There was very little support for the Pacific fleet at the
time. He said, `We were expendable.' Human lives didn't mean that
much at the time,'' she said.
   After the war, Kelly taught marine engineering at the Naval
Academy and served at the Naval War College. He retired from the
Navy in 1961 after having served as deputy chief of staff of the
Navy's Caribbean command.
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by two sons and one
daughter. Funeral services will Monday at Memorial Chapel at
Arlington National Cemetery, followed by a graveside service with
full military honors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890128-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 1708EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Cambodia     01-28 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>India To Broaden Role in Cambodian Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India will step up its efforts to end the
Cambodian conflict by sending a Cabinet minister to Indonesia to
take part in next month's informal peace talks, news reports said
Saturday.
   The Press Trust of India said K. Natwar Singh, minister of state
for external affairs, will leave Sunday for Jakarta, the Indonesian
capital.
   Singh's departure was announced a day after Vietnamese leader
Nguyen Van Linh ended a five-day visit to New Delhi.
   Linh, secretary-general of Vietnam's Communist Party, told
reporters Friday that India ``deserves a major role (in the peace
talks) because it is on the side of the developing countries and
newly independent nations.''
   The second round of informal talks aimed at the withdrawal of
Vietnamese troops from Cambodia are to be held from Feb. 10-21 in
Jakarta. At least one of three factions opposing the Hanoi-backed
Cambodian government and the six members of the noncommunist
Association of South East Nations will attend.
   Resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk has said he will not
attend the meeting because Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen rejected
his proposal that an international peacekeeping force supervise the
withdrawal of Vietnamese forces.
   Preparations for the meeting were continuing and Indonesia is
awaiting word whether Sihanouk's son, Norodom Nararidh, will head
the delegation of his father's faction, Indonesian Foreign Minister
Ali Alatas said in Jakarta.
   The Khmer Rouge faction has not confirmed its attendance but Son
Sann, the leader of the third resistance group, will participate in
the talks, Alatas said.
   Vietnamese, Laotian and Cambodian delegations will also attend
the discussions.
   Vietnamese troops invaded Cambodia in 1978 and set up a pro-Hanoi
government in Phnom Penh. Vietnam says it will pull its 50,000
troops out of Cambodia by 1990 or perhaps sooner if a political
solution is reached.
   The Association of South East Asian Nations, which supports the
three-faction resistance coalition, groups Brunei, Indonesia,
Singapore, Malaysia, Thailand and the Philippines.
</TEXT>
