<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     01-28 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq Wants U.N. To Set Date For Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations should arbitrarily set a
date for resuming Persian Gulf peace talks despite objections from
Iran, Iraq's foreign minister said Saturday.
   Tariq Aziz called on the U.N. officials to pressure Iran into
returning to the negotiating table.
   ``The secretary-general and his personal representative are
duty-bound now to fix a date for resuming the peace talks at a date
which they find appropriate, and they should not allow Iran to put
any preconditions on resumption of talks,'' Aziz said, according to
the official Iraqi News Agency.
   Tariq Aziz comments came at the end of the first day of talks
with a team of U.N. officials headed by special envoy Jan Eliasson,
who arrived from Tehran Friday on a mission to revive the stalled
negotations.
   A spokesman for the U.N. delegation, Gianni Picco, would not
comment on the content of Saturday's discussions or say whether the
face-to-face negotiations would resume soon.
   ``We are working to make progress in implementing U.N. Resolution
598,'' he said, referring to the Security Council resolution that
outlined a cease-fire and peace treaty in the 8-year gulf war.
   ``We will leave no stone unturned in trying to achieve that,'' he
added.
   A U.N.-sponsored cease-fire in the gulf war took effect Aug. 20
but peace talks that began five days later in Geneva broke down
immediately over the issue of troop withdrawals to prewar borders.
   Two further rounds of negotiations brought no progress and no
date was set for them to resume.
   Earlier this week, Eliasson, held four days of talks in Iran with
officials there.
   Iran has demanded that before the peace talks resume, the two
sides should agree to full implementation of Resolution 598,
including the troop withdrawals.
   The U.N. resolution calls on Iran and Iraq to ``halt all military
activities'' and honor the truce, withdraw troops to pre-war
borders, exchange around 100,000 prisoners of war and start peace
talks.
   Iran has accused Baghdad of blocking a peace agreement by
refusing to withdraw from Iranian territory, but Iraq says it will
not pull out until Iran gives up the right to search Iraq-bound
ships in the gulf for war cargo.
</TEXT>
