<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 1726EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     01-28 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0417</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Tenth Candidate For Parliament Killed ^By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese extremists shot and killed a
candidate for next month's Parliament election, bringing to 10 the
number of candidates slain this month, officials said Saturday.
   Punchibanda Ratnayake was shot to death Friday night in Welimadu,
about 75 miles east of Colombo, police said, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   Ratnayake, a Sinhalese, was a member of the opposition Sri Lanka
Freedom Party.
   A senior election department official said 10 candidates for the
Feb. 15 parliamentary elections have been killed since nominations
closed Jan. 6.
   Police had put the total at 10 before Ratnayake was killed. But
the election official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
that was incorrect.
   He said six of the slain candidates belonged to the Freedom
Party, two to the leftist United Socialist Alliance, one to
President Ranasinghe Premadasa's governing United National Party and
one to the Sri Lanka Tamil Congress party.
   Seven of the victims were Sinhalese, two were Tamils and one was
Moslem.
   Police blamed the latest killing and most of the others on the
People's Liberation Front, an extremist Sinhalese group. However,
they said two Tamil candidates killed in the northern Jaffna region
were victims of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, a separatist
guerrilla group that has been fighting the government since 1983.
   Both the Tigers and the People's Liberation Front have vowed to
disrupt the elections for the 225-seat Parliament.
   Police said the front has killed more than 60 people, most of
them political party supporters, in the last three days.
   The Tigers have rejected the government's offer of partial
autonomy for northern and eastern Sri Lanka, where most Tamils live.
The Tigers are seeking an independent homeland for their ethnic
minority.
   The People's Liberation Front started attacking the government
and other Sinhalese politicians last year, saying too many
concessions were being made to the Tamil minority.
   Sinhalese make up about 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million
people and dominate the government and military. Tamils comprise
about 18 percent and say they are discriminated against by the
Sinhalese.
   Most Tamils are Hindus, and most Sinhalese are Buddhists.
   The Moslems, who claim descent from Arab traders, account for
about 7 percent of the population.
   There is also a tiny Christian minority, consisting of
descendants of European colonists and converts among the Sinhalese
and Tamil communities.
</TEXT>
