<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Women     01-28 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Women,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khamenei: Women In The West Are Pleasure Objects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian President Ali Khamenei deplored
the plight of women in Western society on Saturday and said their
real rights are safeguarded only by Islam, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
   ``In stark contrast to the honor and respect accorded to women in
Islam, the West has degraded women to the meanest level,'' the news
agency quoted Khamenei as saying.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted him as saying that women
in the West have been reduced to ``mere objects of pleasure,''
despite alleged strides toward achieving equal rights.
   The Iranian president was speaking at the opening of a seminar on
women held to mark the anniversary of the birth of Fatima, daughter
of the Prophet Mohammed who founded the Islamic faith.
   Khamenei criticized the Western ``culture of permissiveness and
nudity which gives man a free rein to exploit and insult woman's
personality,'' the agency said.
   Despite official claims that under the Islamic regime, Iranian
women enjoy more rights than ever, women are still considered
second-class citizens in Iran and are strictly segregated from men
in public.
   One of the first decrees of the Islamic revolution that overthrew
the Western-oriented government of the late Shah Mohammad Reza
Pahlavi 10 years ago was that women should cover themselves from
head to foot in public.
   Iran's revolutionary leader, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, also
reduced the legal age for women to marry from 18 to 13 soon after
coming to power in 1979.
   The tradition of ``siqeh,'' a form of legalized prostitution
which was frowned on by the Shah and is condoned by the Islamic
government, has become common practice in Iran.
   Permitted by Shiite Islam, the largest breakaway sect from the
orthodox Sunni Islam, the practice of ``siqeh'' allows ``a temporary
marriage of a night, a week, a month or a year,'' between men and
women.
   Under Islam, a man is also allowed four wives, but a woman is
only allowed one husband.
</TEXT>
