<FIRST>r i AM-WarCriminals     01-28 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-War Criminals,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historian Says Freed War Criminals Responsible For Anne Frank's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Nazi war criminals freed after
43 years of imprisonment in the Netherlands were indirectly
responsible for sending Anne Frank to the death camps, a historian
said Saturday.
   But there is no direct link between the Dutch Jewish girl who
died in the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp and the two Germans,
said Loe de Jong, considered the nation's foremost authority on
World War II.
   Franz Fischer, 87, and 79-year-old Ferdinand aus der Fuenten were
deported to West Germany on Friday. The two were high-ranking Nazi
officials responsible for sending thousands of Dutch Jews to their
deaths during World War II.
   Only 6,000 of the Netherlands' 150,000 Jews survived Nazi
persecution.
   ``The group that arrested the (Frank) family in Amsterdam
operated under the command of aus der Fuenten and aus der Fuenten
worked under the instructions of Fischer,'' De Jong told The
Associated Press.
   ``It would be correct to say they had indirect responsibility''
for Anne Frank's fate.
   De Jong is the author of the 14-volume ``History of the Kingdom
of the Netherlands in World War II,'' a government-commissioned
study.
   Anne Frank and her family were arrested by a German police unit
known as the Green Police in August 1944, and were first deported to
the Auschwitz death camp in Nazi-held Poland.
   Anne later was moved to the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp in
Germany, where she died of pneumonia in 1945 at age 15.
   From June 1942 until her arrest, Anne wrote her diary as the
Franks hid in a secret section of an Amsterdam canal house closed
off from the rest of the building by a bookshelf.
   The book, perhaps the most famous personal document to come out
of the Holocaust, was published in 1947 and was turned into a play
and movie.
   Fischer ran the Hague-based Jewish Section of the Nazi Security
Service (SS). In that capacity, ``he gave guidelines ... about which
Jews should be rounded up,'' De Jong said.
   Aus der Fuenten, an SS administrator who ran what was cynically
called the Central Directorate for Jewish Emigration, oversaw the
deportations of thousands of Jews from Amsterdam, Rotterdam and The
Hague.
   Fischer and aus der Fuenten were sentenced to death in 1950, but
their sentences were commuted to life imprisonment a year later.
   They were the world's only war criminals who had been jailed
since World War II, according to the government, which said keeping
them here any longer would violate the principle of equality before
the law.
   The Netherlands has pardoned and freed 107 other war criminals
who had been sentenced to death.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890128-0144 </DOCNO>
