<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     01-28 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Flee Funeral of Anti-Apartheid Doctor, Botha Improving</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JOH1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mourners at the funeral of a
slain anti-apartheid leader on Saturday chased away police who tried
to remove a banner bearing the name of an outlawed political group.
   An estimated 5,000 people attended the funeral of Dr. Abu Baker
Asvat, a physician and a founding member of the Azanian Peoples
Organization. He was fatally shot in his medical office Friday in
the black township of Soweto.
   About a dozen white policemen in civilian clothes arrived at the
Avalon Cemetery, which is shared by Soweto and the Indian township
of Lenasia, and tried to pull away a banner with the group's name on
it from four mourners.
   Men began chanting in Arabic, ``God is great,'' and descending on
the policemen, some of whom pulled their guns. The officers then
turned and ran toward their van and drove away.
   No motive is known for the killing of Asvat, an Indian doctor who
ran programs for squatters and homeless people and participated in
education and health programs in Soweto.
   Police and relatives said two black men entered the doctor's
offices, one pretending to be a patient and giving a false name.
They left, returned later with a gun and fired two shots at Asvat,
killing him immediately, then fled.
   Leaders of the banned Azanian Peoples Organization, which
believes blacks should fight for their own political rights without
white help, blamed ``agents of the apartheid system'' for Asvat's
death in speeches at the funeral.
   The group is one of more than 30 anti-apartheid groups the
government banned in 1988.
   Meanwhile, a building housing three black trade unions in East
London, in the eastern Cape province, was gutted by fire Saturday
morning, the South African Press Association reported. It was the
fourth arson attack in as many months against black trade union
offices in the city.
   Police in the black homeland of Ciskei, near East London,
reported four bombs exploded Friday at a small airplane factory and
a post office. No one was injured.
   President P.W. Botha, recovering from a stroke he suffered 10
days before, walked around the garden of his Cape Town residence
Saturday and is recovering ``remarkably quickly,'' his medical team
reported.
   The 73-year-old Botha has been advised to rest for at least five
weeks, the doctors said in a statement.
   He has named Constitutional Development Minister Chris Heunis as
acting president and Heunis will open Parliament on Friday in a
subdued ceremony without the usual parades and pomp, the government
announced.
</TEXT>
