<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 1900EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Yeats     01-28 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeats,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famed Poet Remembered On 50th Anniversary of His Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DRUMCLIFF, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Admirers of the great Irish poet and
playwright William Butler Yeats filled Drumcliff Church on Saturday
to mark the 50th anniversary of his death and remember his literary
legacy.
   A lone army piper played a lament and a choristers from a local
school sang as Yeats' son and daughter, Michael and Anne Yeats,
joined in the memorial service.
   On the poet's grave in the churchyard lay a single rose and a
wreath from the Yeats Society, bearing the brief inscription
``Memories.''
   Yeats, a founder of Dublin's renowned Abbey Theater and winner of
the 1923 Nobel Prize in literature, died in France on Jan. 28, 1939,
at the age of 73 and was buried there temporarily.
   After World War II, his body was returned to Ireland for burial
in a state funeral in 1948 where he wished to be buried _ at
Drumcliff in the shadow of Ben Bulben mountain by the church where
his grandfather had been rector.
   Archbishop of Dublin Donald Caird told the congregation: ``World
acclaim, the Nobel Prize and the offer to have his body buried in
St. Patrick's Cathedral in Dublin did not prevail against the poet's
simple wish to be buried in Drumcliff churchyard.''
   The churchyard is mentioned in Yeats' 1938 poem ``Under Ben
Bulben,'' which reads in part: ``Under bare Ben Bulben's head, in
Drumcliff churchyard Yeats is laid.''
   Yeat's epitaph, which he chose from the same poem, is seen by
thousands of visitors who pay their respects each year in this
County Sligo hamlet at the head of Drumcliff Bay on the west coast
of Ireland:
   ``Cast a cold Eye
   ``On Life, on Death
   ``Horseman, pass by!''
   Dublin-born Yeats was an ardent nationalist and traditionalist
who served as a senator in the Irish Free State from 1922 to 1928,
helped found the Irish National Theater Company, and with George
Bernard Shaw and poet-economist G.W. Russell founded the Irish
Academy of Letters in 1932.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890128-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 1905EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     01-28 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary Likely To Drop ``People's Republic'' From Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is likely to shed its
``people's republic'' designation and adopt its pre-communist coat
of arms, the Hungarian state news agency MTI reported.
   A parliamentary committee rewriting the constitution is
considering the move, as well as including human rights provisions
and political reform in the document that will likely be approved by
a voter referendum, the news agency said late Friday.
   Members of the panel said it was ``quite superfluous'' to add
epithets such as ``democratic'' or ``socialist'' to the designation
``republic of Hungary'' in a new constitution now being prepared,
MTI said Friday.
   Hungary's present official name is Magyar Nepkoeztarsasag or
Hungarian People's Republic. That name will be changed in the new
constitution, MTI said.
   Lawyers on the committee argued the constitution, not the
designation of the state, should reflect the democratic and
socialist system in Hungary, the news agency said.
   Lawmakers also proposed that the first chapter of the
constitution should lay down human rights and obligations, MTI
reported.
   Several deputies said a coat of arms, including the St. Stephen's
crown, which is kept in Parliament, would be the most suitable
symbol of statehood, while others favored the Kossuth coat of arms,
which does not contain the crown.
   The current Hungarian coat of arms was fashioned after the Soviet
model, featuring two sheaves forming a circle.
   The Kossuth coat of arms was used for a while in the wake of the
1848 uprising against Hapsburg rule.
   Constitutional committee members agreed that the prime minister
should in future be elected by Parliament and be obliged to
introduce his government to the chamber, MTI said.
   They also supported the idea that the president of the republic
should have genuine powers but he should not be entitled to dissolve
parliament, because a strong presidential system might lead toward a
personality cult.
   MTI quoted Justice Minister Kalman Kulcsar as saying that the
draft of the constitution would be discussed by various
organizations, including alternative groups outside the ruling
Communist Party, in the coming weeks.
   After going before the party's policy-setting Central Committee
and then parliament on March 8, the text of the constitution will be
completed by June 8, presented ``for public debate'' in the second
half of the year and again submitted to Parliament in December this
year.
   ``If Parliament approves the new constitution, it will most
probably be subject to a referendum,'' MTI said.
</TEXT>
