<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Rebels     01-28 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Rebels,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Abandons Town After Nine-Month Rebel Onslaught</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defending government troops ran out of
ammunition and abandoned a southern Sudanese town besieged by rebels
for more than nine months, the army's general command said Saturday.
   The army statement said more than 1,700 army and rebel troops
were killed or wounded in the 37-week siege of Nasir in Upper Nile
region.
   The statement said the government troops were forced to withdraw
after bad weather stopped airdrops of much-needed ammunition and
supplies. Since the siege started, army aircraft have been dropping
supplies over the town and bombing rebel camps around it.
   In Addis Ababa, Sudan People's Liberation Organization spokesman,
Lam Akol, said the rebels had captured the strategic town after
seven days of intensive fighting and that they were in full control
of the garrison town.
   ``People are now rejoicing and dancing in the streets of the
city,'' Akol said.
   Six other government garrisons fell in recent months. In each
case the army explained the loss as a ``tactical withdrawal'' of its
forces.
   Nasir is about 500 miles south of Khartoum and 20 miles from
Sudan's border with Ethiopia, which has aided the rebels with
weapons, money and facilities since the uprising began in 1983.
   Nasir's loss is a major blow to the beleaguered Sudanese army's
war effort. Western military sources said late last year that in
rebel hands, Nasir would become a springboard for attacks on central
and western Upper Nile.
   The army statement said the Sudanese armed forces ``decided to
withdraw its troops from Nasir effective yesterday (Friday) after
they ran out of ammunition and it became impossible for them to
defend the town any further.
   ``It became totally impossible to supply the town with equipment
and men.''
   More than 1,000 ``outlaw forces'' _ government jargon for bush
fighters of the Sudan People's Liberation Army _ were killed or
wounded during the siege, the statement said. It put government
losses at more than 100 soldiers killed and more than 600 wounded.
   Army dead included Col. Mahjoub Mohammed Moussa, commander of the
Nasir garrison, ``whose plane crashed last week,'' the statement
said without giving details. Neither did it specify whether the
plane was shot by rebels.
   The rebel broadcast from Ethiopia claimed that Moussa was
captured when his men fled during the ``one hour of storm attack''
that finally took Nasir. ``SPLA forces are now in hot pursuit of the
remnants, who fled in disarray in different directions,'' the
broadcast said.
   Renegade army Col. John Garang formed the guerrilla army and
launched his rebellion against the Moslem-dominated central
government in early 1983.
   Rebel operations cover all southern Sudan's three regions of
Equatoria, Bahr el-Ghazal and Upper Nile, inhabited mostly by
Christians and animists. Garang wants economic and administrative
reforms in the south.
</TEXT>
