<FIRST>r i AM-Portugal-Labor     01-28 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Portugal-Labor,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Protest Government Labor Package That Allows More Layoffs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands supporting a
communist-dominated trade union marched through the capital Saturday
protesting a labor law package proposed by the center-right
government that would permit more layoffs.
   The estimated 20,000 demonstrators, waving banners and chanting
slogans dating from the country's 1974 leftist revolution, filed
slowly along downtown Lisbon's main boulevard Avenida da Liberdade
and into Rossio central square.
   They called for an eight-hour reduction in the present 48-hour
working week and a 13.5-percent increase in the national minimum
salary recently hiked to around $200 per month.
   The General Confederation of Portuguese Workers (CGTP),
Portugal's most powerful union, organized the march and other
gatherings across the country against laws they claim would allow
employers to hire and fire at will and deprive workers of job
security by the spread of temporary contracts.
   Anibal Cavaco Silva's Social Democratic government says the laws
are necessary that allow employers to dismiss workers for economic
reasons, in order to streamline the work force in Portugal's
labor-intensive and state-dominated economy.
   A socialist-inspired constitution adopted after the 1974
revolution currently makes it difficult for employers to dismiss
workers.
   Unions and employers' associations were initially slated to sign
an accord on the package Monday but the signing was called off, as
neither side could agree to final terms.
   The Socialist-associated General Union of Workers (UGT) had
worked out an agreement with the government, but it was later
rejected by employers.
   Both UGT and CGTP unions also object to a wages and prices
proposal based on what they see as unrealistic government forecasts
on inflation and have threatened a general strike if no acceptable
labor package can be found.
   The government based last year's wage claims on an inflation
prediction of around 6 percent. Inflation nearly hit an annualized
10 percent at the end of December.
   Cavaco Silva points out Portugal's growth rate of an estimated
4.2 percent in 1988 is almost double the European Economic Community
average and a 6 percent unemployment rate is relatively low for EEC
standards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
