<FIRST>u a AM-HotelFire 3rdLd-Writethru a0612 01-28 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hotel Fire, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0612,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bethlehem Hotel Fire Leaves Three Dead, 14 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to add background and details.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ALN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A smoky fire erupted Saturday in the middle
of a landmark nine-story hotel, killing at least three people and
injuring 14, officials said.
   The fire started about 7:15 a.m. in a fifth-floor room at the
Bethlehem Hotel, and spread to the hallway and an adjoining room
before being extinguished before noon.
   Floors above suffered smoke damage and the fourth floor suffered
water damage, Fire Commissioner Carmen Oliver said. Robert Decker,
who owns the hotel with his wife, Dee, estimated damage in the
millions of dollars.
   Among those staying at the hotel were 20 residents of a nearby
apartment building for the elderly that was being renovated. Others
were business travelers and music teachers attending a convention.
   The fire started in the room of Murial Brooks of Croton Falls,
N.Y.
   ``I plugged an iron into the wall socket and there was a flash.
The chair caught fire and I tried to beat it out,'' said Brooks, who
was not injured.
   Oliver said officials had not yet ruled on the cause of the fire.
   ``There was no fire alarm, there was no sound,'' said Bob
Gregory, who was staying on the fifth floor while on business. ``I
knew where the door was and I could feel where the smoke was coming
from,'' he said in describing his escape.
   The Deckers said the fire alarms did sound and four hotel
employees went upstairs to knock on doors and alert the guests.
   ``We had four people who said (the alarms) were definitely going
off,'' Mrs. Decker said. ``The fire system is excellent. We updated
it when we bought the hotel four years ago.''
   ``You could see the flames going out the window,'' said Ruth
Edwards, who was staying on the ninth floor and attending Eastern
Division convention of the Music Teachers National Association.
   At least 100 rooms in the 126-room hotel were occupied by people
attending the convention, Mrs. Decker said.
   The hotel, which opened in 1922 and has been renovated in recent
years, also is the site of major social events in this eastern
Pennsylvania city about 60 miles north of Philadelphia.
   Two of the dead were identified as Monique Forbes, 58, who lived
at the hotel, and John Kelly, 75, a resident of the Monocacy Towers
retirement home, said County Coroner Joseph Reichel. The third
victim was identified as Charles R. Knouse, 69, said Lehigh County
Coroner Wayne Snyder.
   Six people were taken to St. Luke's Hospital for treatment,
including a 65-year-old woman from the retirement home who was in
critical condition. Six victims were taken to Muhlenberg Hospital
and two, ages 79 and 83, were in critical condition, said
spokeswoman Melissa Wright.
   An Easton Hospital spokeswoman, Faith Jendzeizwk, said two
victims were treated there and released.
   Three firefighters suffered minor injuries, Oliver said.
</TEXT>
