<FIRST>u a AM-NoahRobinson 1stLd-Writethru a0620 01-28 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Noah Robinson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0620,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robinson Convicted On Felony Charge; Mistrial Declared on Murder
Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with reaction from Robinson; defense
attorneys saying they will appeal and appeal bond set; Robinson still in
custody; picking up 8th graf pvs: `Robinson was...'; INSERTS 2 grafs after
11th graf pvs: `Earlier, defense...' with reaction from defense attorney;
picks up 12th graf pvs: `During the...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago millionaire Noah Robinson was
sentenced to the maximum 10 years in prison Saturday after being
found guilty of a felony in connection with the attempted murder of
a woman who witnessed a slaying.
   Robinson, half-brother of the Rev. Jesse Jackson and a Greenville
native, was charged with murder and conspiracy in the death of Leroy
``Hambone'' Barber. State Circuit Judge James Moore declared a
mistrial on those counts when the jury failed to reach a verdict.
   The jury convicted Robinson of accessory after the fact of
assault and battery with intent to kill in connection with the
attempted murder of Janice Denise Rosemond.
   Robinson, 45, was accused of hiring someone to kill Ms. Rosemond,
who witnessed the 1986 murder of Barber. Ms. Rosemond survived a
stabbing attack.
   Moore sentenced Robinson to 10 years in prison, and Robinson was
led away in handcuffs to the Greenville County Detention Center.
   ``I've said all along I'm innocent of the charges but I'm
prepared to take the punishment the court will mete on me,''
Robinson said during sentencing.
   Moore declared a mistrial for the four other charges _ murder and
conspiracy to commit murder in the Barber slaying and criminal
conspiracy and accessory before the fact of assault and battery with
intent to kill in connection with the Rosemond attack.
   Solicitor Joe Watson, the prosecutor, said Robinson will face
another trial on those charges.
   Defense attorneys said they would appeal the conviction and an
appeal bond of $100,000 was set. Moore also reinstated bond of $1
million on the other charges. Robinson remained in custody late
Saturday, officials said.
   Robinson was accused of hiring members of the El Rukn gang of
Chicago to come to Greenville to kill Barber, a former employee and
childhood friend.
   Before beginning deliberations Saturday, the jury asked the judge
what would happen if they reached a verdict on only some of the
charges. Moore told the jurors a mistrial would be called only on
those indictments they couldn't decide.
   The jury spent 16 hours deliberating. The trial began Jan. 16.
   Earlier, defense attorney Robert Simone asked that one of the
jurors be removed because Watson had coached the woman's children on
a swim team. Moore denied the request.
   Simone said he was ``really upset about the sentence'' but said
there was ``logic behind that verdict.''
   ``I think the jury probably inferred'' that Robinson knew about
the attack on Ms. Rosemond, Simone said. ``But they did not reach a
conclusion that he was involved before or during the incident,'' he
said.
   During the trial Watson traced the history of Chicago's El Rukn
gang and its ties to Robinson.
   Witnesses testified that Robinson was a close friend of Jeff
Fort, the leader of the gang, who is serving time in a Texas prison
on drug charges. Witnesses also testified that Robinson wielded a
significant amount of power in the organization.
   Watson told the jury of Robinson's stormy relationship with
Barber, with whom Robinson had physically fought and whom Robinson
believed broke into buildings he owned in Chicago.
   Simone said Robinson was a victim of a misguided investigation.
The attorney argued that prosecutors had made deals with known
criminals, who in testifying ``to save their own skin'' had
implicated an innocent man.
</TEXT>
