<FIRST>u a AM-ShipAbandoned     01-28 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ship Abandoned,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search Fails to Find Crew Of Japanese Cargo Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard and Navy searched the
northern Pacific Ocean on Saturday for a Japanese cargo ship's crew,
which apparently abandoned the vessel during a storm off the
Aleutian Islands.
   The Port Star sent a distress call to Japanese marine safety
officials Saturday morning, saying cargo on the deck of the 850-foot
vessel was lost and the 20-member crew was abandoning ship, said
Coast Guard spokesman Chris Haley.
   Coast Guard officials said the Port Star was caught in 30- to
40-foot seas and winds of 65 to 75 knots, or approximately 75-85
mph, at the time of the distress message.
   Japanese officials alerted the Coast Guard in Juneau and a P-3
aircraft from the Navy installation at Adak in the Aleutians began a
search. The Aleutians are a chain of islands that extend southwest
off the Alaska mainland.
   Haley said the Navy reported no sign of the crew aboard the
vessel, which was still afloat some 300 miles southwest of Attu in
the Aleutian chain.
   He said only one life raft remained aboard.
   The Port Star is owned by Nipponkai Steamship Co. Ltd. of Tokyo
and was transporting logs. The Coast Guard did not know the ship's
destination.
   Saturday's search was hampered by poor weather and visibility and
the search was expected to resume Sunday morning. Haley said the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration ship Miller Freeman
is expected to reach the scene late Sunday.
   A Coast Guard C-130 aircraft was unable to leave the ground in
Kodiak because of severe weather Saturday, Haley said. The Coast
Guard cutter Yacona was diverted and probably will not reach the
area of the Port Star's location until late Monday, he said.
</TEXT>
