<DOCNO> AP890128-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-28-89 2337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-HazardousLeak 1stLd-Writethru a0607 01-28 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hazardous Leak, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sulfur Dioxide Forces Evacuation In Idaho Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with evacuation over; crews venting
the tank, picks up 7th graf pvs: ```It was...'; SUBS 8th graf pvs: `At
least...' to UPDATE number of injured to nine.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONNERS FERRY, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A railroad tanker filled with sulfur
dioxide leaked Saturday, spewing hazardous fumes with the stench of
rotten eggs and forcing evacuation of hundreds of people from the
downtown area for several hours.
   Authorities said the Union Pacific tanker car was on a siding
near the Boundary County Fairgrounds, adjacent to downtown, when it
sprang a two- to three-inch hole shortly after 6:30 a.m.
   An estimated 400 to 500 people, some elderly, were forced out of
businesses and homes, and sheriff's officers maintained roadblocks
to keep people out.
   Residents were allowed to return about 3:30 p.m., but were warned
they should leave again if they smelled any fumes, said Allen
Chrisman, a U.S. Forest Service official.
   ``Things are looking good,'' Chrisman said. ``All the folks have
been returned to their homes.''
   Among the evacuees was Boundary County Clerk Norma Estep, who
said there was no panic and praised civil defense personnel who
responded to the evacuation order.
   ``Our emergency crews did an excellent job,'' Mrs. Estep said.
``I'm really proud of them.''
   The tanker continued to leak Saturday afternoon, but Robert
Heffner of the state Communications and Poison Control Center in
Boise said it had been moved about five miles south of town and a
nearby farm house was evacuated as a precaution.
   Crews were venting the gas through barrels of lime to neutralize
the sulfur dioxide, Chrisman said. The crews planned to monitor the
situation through the night and eventually transfer the material to
another tank car.
   ``It was pretty thick this morning, but it's a lot clearer now,''
Jeannie Alonzo, a sheriff's dispatcher, said late Saturday morning.
``It just hurt to breath it.''
   Nine people people were treated for minor eye irritation and
respiratory problems at Boundary County Community Hospital, then
released, a nursing supervisor said. One person with a history of
respiratory ailments was admitted for observation.
   Another person who was downtown at the time of the leak later
died of a heart attack at the hospital, but officials were uncertain
if the death was related to the leak.
   Downtown residents were taken to the local high school and to a
Methodist church at the south end of town on a hill, sheriff's
spokeswoman Jane Kirby said. All the evacuees later were moved to
the church in the town of about 2,000 in the Idaho Panhandle, 26
miles south of the Canadian border.
   The rupture apparently resulted from a structural failure caused
by corrosion, said Scott Lund, a compliance supervisor for the state
Division of Environmental Quality's Hazardous Materials Bureau.
   A hazardous materials team from the Spokane, Wash., Fire
Department was on the scene, assessing the danger and beginning a
cleanup. A hazardous materials response team from British Columbia
also was sent, along with officials from the state Division of
Environmental Quality, the federal Environmental Protection Agency
and Union Pacific.
   Sulfur dioxide is a heavy, colorless, suffocating gas used as a
bleach, disinfectant, refrigerant or preservative. It also is used
in paper pulping and food processing.
   It is liquefied under pressure for shipping. Heffner said the
leak sent a bluish plume of vapor into the air, but the weight of
the gas kept it close to the ground.
   Prolonged exposure to the gas, which has a rotten-egg smell, can
cause nausea, vomiting or even death. When mixed with water, sulfur
dioxide forms a corrosive acid but Heffner said there did not appear
to be any immediate environmental danger.
   The tanker originated in Trail, British Columbia, and was bound
for Trentwood, Wash., near Spokane, said John Bromley, a Union
Pacific spokesman in Omaha, Neb. Lund said the sulfur dioxide was
the property of Cominco American.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
